<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Edwards: 70 Years in Broadcasting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Ralph Edwards, this is your life.  
</P>
<P>
	Edwards, who created the game show ``Truth or Consequences'' and  
produces TV's ``People's Court,'' has been in broadcasting for 70 
years -- and he's still going strong. 
</P>
<P>
	He stays fit, goes to the office three times a week and, at age  
86, looks back to 1929 when he broke into radio as a 16-year-old 
student from a high school in Oakland, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``The changes in both radio and television are mind-boggling,''  
he said. ``In the early days of radio, everything was live ... and 
up until 1948 my weekly radio show, 'Truth or Consequences' was 
done twice each Saturday. When originating in New York, it would be 
done live at 8 o'clock for the East Coast and three hours later 
another live show for the West Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would use the same script but all new contestants.''  
</P>
<P>
	Then came television.  
</P>
<P>
	``Amazingly enough I did 'Truth or Consequences' on television  
in July 1941. It was the first commercial show for NBC,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It featured commercials for Bulova watches. ``A ten-second  
commercial was $9,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	World War II came five months later, and broadcast careers were  
interrupted along with everything else. Resuming after the war, TV 
underwent sweeping change. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen many changes and enjoyed them all,'' Edwards said.  
``I still find 'live' the most exciting, particularly for my type 
of shows.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1950, ``Truth or Consequences'' was sponsored on TV by  
Phillip Morris Tobacco. Edwards says Phillip Morris didn't like 
Kinescope, a format that allowed delayed West Coast telecasts. So 
Edwards broke ground with the ``live on film'' concept. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was revolutionary -- in fact, so sensational that the 'I  
Love Lucy' people used it when they made their television debut the 
following year,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	``Truth or Consequences'' contestants were asked goofy questions  
and had to pay for missed answers by performing goofy stunts. The 
show lasted a single season with Edwards as host and then returned 
in 1954 with Jack Bailey as host. Other emcees included Steve Dunne 
and Bob Barker, who made a career of the popular show. 
</P>
<P>
	The show became enormously popular and producers were even able  
to persuade the New Mexico town of Hot Springs to change its name 
to Truth or Consequences as part of the show's 1950 promotion 
effort. 
</P>
<P>
	While ``Truth or Consequences'' lived on without Edwards, he  
went on to do ``This Is Your Life,'' which featured guests who did 
not know they were about to be confronted with their pasts. It ran 
on NBC-TV from 1952 to 1961. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards produced or co-produced an array of other shows,  
including ``Name That Tune,'' ``Place the Face,'' ``End of the 
Rainbow'' and ``The Wide Country,'' a Western. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, Edwards starts his mornings with juice and oatmeal,  
but ``strange as it seems I have never drunk coffee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He confers with his partner in Ralph Edwards/Stu Billett  
Productions, reviews tape and makes suggestions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so lucky,'' Billett says. ``He's had shows on that lasted  
for so many years. ... He's got great instincts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards has reviewed and approves of Jerry Sheindlin, who  
started this month as the judge on ``People's Court,'' Billett 
says. Sheindlin, husband of Judy Sheindlin of ``Judge Judy'' fame, 
spent 17 years on the bench in the Bronx. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards was born in Merino, Colo., and worked at KROW and KFRC  
in San Francisco while attending the University of California at 
Berkeley. He now lives in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards' wife, Barbara, died in 1993. He remains in almost daily  
contact with his children, Gary, who works with him; and daughters 
Christine Tandy in Salem, Ore., and Laurie Lenhart in Los Gatos, 
Calif. He has four grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	And every few weeks he has dinner with his friend and colleague,  
Bob Barker. 
</P>
<P>
	Barker said Edwards gave him the defining break of his career  
when he picked him for ``Truth or Consequences'' on Dec. 21, 1956 -- 
``the most exciting Christmas of my life.'' The two have met every 
Dec. 21 to celebrate, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards is ``a splendid host, an excellent producer, a very  
talented writer -- but beyond all that he's a wonderful man,'' 
Barker said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In 43 years of television, I have never heard one person ever  
say anything derogatory about Ralph Edwards.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	BUYER BEWARE: The average person is exposed to more than 3,000  
ads each day, researchers estimate. ``Spin &AMP; Sell: A History of 
Advertising,'' showing 9 p.m. EDT Friday on History Channel's 
``Time Machine,'' shows how advertising works and how ads influence 
more than our buying decisions. Dick Cavett narrates the two-hour 
special and Roger Mudd is host. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
