<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marshall-Toledo Play in Prime Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Chad Pennington has been fashionably  
late for Marshall's game with Toledo the last two years. The 
Rockets hope he doesn't show up at all this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo (3-2, 1-2 MAC West) will get its final shot at the  
Mid-American Conference's career passing leader Thursday night in 
the first MAC regular-season game on national TV since 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	This may not be Toledo's best chance. Pennington is having  
another great year and No. 15 Marshall (5-0, 2-0 MAC East) has 19 
starters back. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Chad, you've got an NFL quarterback. What else can you say  
about the guy?'' Toledo coach Gary Pinkel said. ``They're the best 
team I've seen in this league this decade. They might be one of the 
best ever. They are about as strong and sound at every position 
that you can be. Our players recognize that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pennington has completed 63 percent of his passes for 1,569  
yards and 14 touchdowns, ranking him second in Division I-A passing 
efficiency behind Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton. 
</P>
<P>
	The past two years he led Marshall to comeback victories over  
Toledo in the MAC title game in Huntington to earn automatic bids 
to the Motor City Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the year he broke Tim Couch's NCAA record for  
sophomores with 39 TD passes, Pennington threw three second-half 
touchdowns and 322 yards passing in a 34-14 win over the Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, Pennington was hobbled by a groin pull against  
Toledo, but drove Marshall 61 yards for the go-ahead score in the 
fourth quarter of a 23-17 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully we will put it away earlier,'' Pennington said.  
``It's scary going into the fourth quarter not knowing what's going 
to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall's national ranking is the highest for a MAC team since  
Miami of Ohio finished 10th at the end of the 1974 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're the team to beat in the MAC,'' Toledo tight end Mike  
Bilik said. ``They've beat us the past two years. But at the same 
time, we're not going to let that ruin our confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overconfidence could be Marshall's biggest foe.  
</P>
<P>
	Marshall, a 22-point favorite Thursday, owns Division I-A's  
longest home winning streak at 27 games. It also has Division I-A's 
longest overall winning streak at nine games, along with 106 
victories in the 1990s, a record for any decade in Division I-A or 
I-AA. 
</P>
<P>
	The six remaining teams on Marshall's schedule are a combined  
12-22. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a MAC championship game every game, so we've  
got to be ready no matter who we play,'' Pennington said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams have injuries at running back.  
</P>
<P>
	Doug Chapman, seeking to become the first Marshall player to  
rush for 1,000 yards in four straight seasons, has just 296 yards. 
He has played three games with a dislocated right thumb but is 
expected to have a soft cast removed this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo's Chester Taylor, third in the conference with 519 yards,  
is questionable with a sprained ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo quarterback Tavares Bolden will get the nod again this  
week after replacing Dan Cole as the starter in a 47-7 win over 
Kent last week. Both threw for two scores. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just kind of felt we needed a little jolt in our passing  
game,'' Pinkel said. ``This business is based on results.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
