<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of New York VP Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A suspended executive at the Bank of New York  
has resigned, saying she was unfairly victimized by rumors swirling 
around what is alleged to be the largest money laundering scandal 
in U.S. history. 
</P>
<P>
	Natasha Kagalovsky, senior vice president and head of the bank's  
Eastern European Division, said Tuesday in her resignation letter 
that she was tired of living in ``professional limbo'' amid 
baseless rumors. She was suspended by the bank Aug. 18. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find this intolerable, personally very hurtful and extremely  
unfair,'' she said in a letter submitted to bank chairman Thomas 
Renyi. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kagalovsky had been on paid leave since the bank became  
publicly embroiled in an alleged massive money laundering scheme in 
which up to $10 billion was illegally moved from Russia through the 
Bank of New York, the nation's 15th-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The money may have ties to the Russia mafia, though Russian  
officials are also eying corporations and individuals trying to 
avoid paying taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Renyi assured employees in an August memo that the bank was  
cooperating with investigators, that it has not been accused of any 
wrongdoing, and that no funds have been lost or customer services 
interrupted. 
</P>
<P>
	Though no action was taken against Ms. Kagalovsky, her future at  
the bank remained unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she was quitting with a heavy heart because nothing  
justified ``leaving me to swing in the wind, when nothing I ever 
did or didn't do was wrong in any way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bank spokesman Frank Scarangella would only say: ``We  
acknowledge the resignation and wish her well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kagalovsky's letter was quoted in a statement released by  
her lawyer, Stanley Arkin. He said his client was willing to 
cooperate with the investigation but had little to offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's always available to give whatever information is  
required,'' he said. ``She is completely uninvolved and 
unknowledgeable about any wrongdoing. She feels this bank should 
have been more supportive of her. We have nothing to hide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kagalovsky was not indicted last month when indictments were  
returned against Lucy Edwards, another executive at the bank, Ms. 
Edwards' husband, Peter Berlin, and their business associate, 
Aleksey Volkov, as well as three companies with which they were 
allegedly involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Edwards, Berlin and Volkov were charged with conspiring from  
1996 through August 1999 of illegally funneling $7 billion from 
Russia through accounts at the Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of New York subsequently fired Ms. Edwards for  
allegedly falsifying records and failing to cooperate with internal 
investigators. She had denied any wrongdoing. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
