<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Get $89M To Fight Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department awarded $89 million in  
grants to Indian communities in 26 states to hire, train and equip 
police officers and to build new jails and detention facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The grants are aimed at reducing crime rates among the 1.4  
million Indians living on or near Indian territories. Government 
studies show Indians are victims of violent crime more than twice 
as often as any other major group and are more likely than others 
to be attacked by people of other races. 
</P>
<P>
	``These grants for additional officers, training and facilities  
will help ensure that all native Americans living on Indian lands 
will enjoy the decrease in crime being felt throughout the 
nation,'' said Attorney General Janet Reno, who met today with 
tribal leaders to discuss crime issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the Bureau of Justice Statistics reported  
that from 1992 through 1996, an annual average of 124 out of every 
1,000 Indians age 12 or older were victims of violent crime. By 
comparison, the rate for whites was 49 per 1,000; and it was 61 for 
blacks and 29 for Asian-Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Developed by the Justice and Interior Departments in  
consultation with tribes, the grants will pay for: 
</P>
<P>
	--Tribal communities to hire more police officers or to train or  
better equip existing ones. 
</P>
<P>
	--New regional jails and detention facilities.  
</P>
<P>
	--Technical assistance to devise new justice systems, such as  
inter-tribal courts to share limited resources. 
</P>
<P>
	--Programs for at-risk youths to combat gang violence and drug  
and domestic abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Intertribal exchanges of ideas will be fostered by a  
``comprehensive Indian resources for community and law enforcement 
project. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian communities awarded grants are located in Alaska,  
Arizona, California, Florida, Indiana, Kansas, Louisiana, Maine, 
Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, Nebraska, New Mexico, 
Nevada, New York, North Dakota, Oklahoma, Oregon, Rhode Island, 
South Dakota, Texas, Utah, Washington, Wisconsin and Wyoming. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
