<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 13, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Indian PM Vajpayee Sworn In  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Amid political upheaval in neighboring  
Pakistan, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee was sworn in 
Wednesday as India's leader for the third time. Vajpayee's 
government fell in April when a southern politician withdrew her 
party's 18 seats from the coalition and Vajpayee lost a confidence 
motion by one vote. No other group was able to form a government 
and Vajpayee remained in charge of a caretaker government while 
elections were held. Vajpayee had said that one of the first tasks 
of his new government would be to restart peace talks that were 
disrupted by recent fighting in Kashmir, which has been the cause 
of two of the three wars between Pakistan and India. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Government Overthrown in Coup  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistani troops staged a coup  
against the democratically elected government Tuesday, seizing 
state-run media and confining the prime minister to his home in a 
lightning move that raised tensions in the world's newest nuclear 
region. In a televised address, Army Chief Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf 
accused the government of ``systematically destroying'' state 
institutions and driving the economy toward collapse. ``You are all 
well aware of the kind of turmoil and uncertainty that our country 
has gone through in recent times,'' Musharraf said. ``Not only have 
all the institutions been played around with and systematically 
destroyed, the economy too is in a state of collapse.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Daily Struggle in Mexico Flood Zone  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN ACATENO, Mexico (AP) -- All they wanted was food for  
themselves and their village. To get it, the 40 men had to trudge 
for three hours along a muddy, damaged road, cross a makeshift 
bridge and shoulder heavy bags of basic foodstuffs. Then, bent 
under their burdens, the return trip to their village, Hueyapan, 
awaited them. It is a scene being repeated across eastern Mexico, 
where a deluge of rain has washed out bridges and roads, isolating 
hundreds of communities and forcing residents to make long journeys 
for food. Efforts to bring in food have been hampered by the 
geographical sweep of the emergency, poor weather, and the need to 
recover the bodies of the dead. 

</P>
<P>
	Wilt Chamberlain Dead At 63  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Basketball Hall of Famer Wilt Chamberlain was  
found dead Tuesday in his Bel-Air home. He was 63 years old. 
Authorities said there were signs that Chamberlain might have had a 
heart attack. Sy Goldberg, Chamberlain's agent, said he had been 
hospitalized with an irregular heartbeat in 1992, and was on 
medication. ``Wilt the Stilt'' played from 1959 to 1973 for the 
Philadelphia (later the San Francisco) Warriors, the Philadelphia 
76ers and the Lakers. He averaged 30.1 points per game. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Rescue Planes Head to S. Pole  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) -- Two Air National Guard Hercules  
LC-130 cargo planes arrived at Antarctica's coast Wednesday, 
positioning themselves for a daring mission to the South Pole to 
rescue an American doctor with a lump in her breast. After a 
24-hour delay caused by bad weather, the two planes set out from 
New Zealand for McMurdo base in Antarctica after high winds and 
swirling snow eased on the frigid continent. ``Weather conditions 
both at and above McMurdo station are favorable, with yesterday's 
high winds and whiteout conditions having cleared away during the 
night,'' said National Science Foundation spokesman Peter West. 

</P>
<P>
	Test Ban Agreement Remains Elusive  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While bipartisan support is building in the  
Senate to delay a nuclear test ban vote, finding a graceful exit 
from near-certain defeat of the pact remains elusive. A small group 
of conservatives continues to threaten to block any effort at 
meeting President Clinton's request that the vote on the 
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty be postponed. Unless a deal can be 
reached, a showdown vote on the pact will occur late today. Clinton 
and other supporters concede they are far short of the 67 needed 
for ratification if all 100 senators vote. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Close Down 336.32  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices closed down on Wednesday. The  
Nikkei plunged 336.32 points to close at 17,754.49. In New York on 
Tuesday, the Dow ended down 231.12 at 10,417.06. 

</P>
<P>
	Piazza Starts, Left Thumb Better  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- New York Mets catcher Mike Piazza was back in his  
accustomed cleanup spot Tuesday night for the opener of the 
best-of-7 National League Championship Series against the Atlanta 
Braves. It didn't help as the Braves beat the Mets 4-2 in Game 1. 
Piazza missed the last two games of the NL division playoffs 
because of a reaction to a cortisone shot to his injured left 
thumb. Piazza, who hit .303 with 40 home runs and 124 RBIs this 
season, said he's about ``95 percent.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
