<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Yen, Tokyo Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar edged up against the yen today, as  
Tokyo stock prices fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded at 106.58 yen by late afternoon, up 0.30 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also above the 106.31 yen level in 
New York. During the day it ranged from 105.93 yen to 106.85 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 336.32 points,  
or 1.86 percent, to close the day at 17,754.49. The index closed up 
28.63 points, or 0.16 percent, Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar initially moved higher on buying  
from Japanese institutional investors, inched down by midafternoon 
and then rose again. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were awaiting the outcome of a Bank of Japan policy  
board meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	At an evening news conference, after financial markets here had  
closed, the central bank said it kept its monetary policy 
unchanged. The central bank will watch the yen carefully because 
its rise could hurt economic recovery in private demand, said BOJ 
Governor Masaru Hayami. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen has soared in recent months on optimism over Japan's  
budding economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar has regained some ground since last month, when  
finance ministers from major countries expressed concern about the 
yen's strength. But the gains have been limited by market 
skepticism about the Bank of Japan's ability to bring the yen back 
down. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial authorities say that too steep a rise in the yen could  
derail the recovery by reducing demand for Japanese goods abroad, 
as a stronger currency makes them more expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan has been struggling to emerge from its worst economic  
downturn in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was trading at 114.87 yen, above  
its level of 113.37 yen late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, share prices fell following a drop on Wall  
Street and caution over the Bank of Japan's policy meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors have adopted a strong wait-and-see attitude,'' said  
Hidenori Karaki, general manager at Tokyo Mitsubishi-Personal 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 658.51 million shares, down from 692.72 million shares 
Tuesday. Retreating issues outnumbered advancers 899 to 320, while 
115 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsuguya Onozuka, an equity futures dealer at Yamatane  
Securities, expects the Nikkei to remain in a narrow range ahead of 
the announcement of a supplementary government budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no major buying or selling incentives,'' Onozuka  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 15.84 points, or 1.03 percent, to finish at 
1,526.96. The TOPIX closed up 11.97 points, or 0.78 percent, on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.7600 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.8000 percent. Its 
price rose 0.34 point to 99.48. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
