<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baby Walkers May Slow Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Baby walkers may be keeping the little one  
occupied and out of trouble, but a new study indicates they could 
also be slowing down the tot's physical and mental development. 
</P>
<P>
	Babies who were placed in walkers were slower to sit up, crawl  
and walk than those raised without walkers, researchers report on 
the current edition of the Journal of Developmental and Behavioral 
Pediatrics. 
</P>
<P>
	And the mental development of the children also appeared to be  
slowed, said the report by Andrea C. Siegel of Case Western Reserve 
University in Cleveland and Roger V. Burton of the State University 
of New York at Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem, the researchers reported, appears to be that the  
opaque trays placed on the newer walkers as a safety device 
prevents the children from seeing their legs -- blocking the 
feedback they get from moving a limb and seeing the leg actually 
move. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, while crawling infants are stimulated by objects in  
their environment, those in walkers are restricted from exploring. 
</P>
<P>
	Many parents think this is good because it can keep baby out of  
trouble, noted Siegel and Burton, but limiting the infant's access 
to objects may have a negative impact on its mental development. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton and Siegel studied 109 suburban infants, mostly white,  
including 53 who did not use walkers, 37 using newer walkers with 
opaque trays that blocked them from seeing their legs and 19 who 
used older walkers with narrow trays or no trays, thus allowing 
them to see their feet. 
</P>
<P>
	On average, they found the infants who did not use walkers were  
able to sit up at age 5.39 months, crawl at 5.84 months and walk at 
10.82 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Those with the older ``see-feet'' walkers sat up at 5.99 months,  
crawled at 6.23 months and walked at 10.70 months. And those with 
new sight-blocking walkers sat up at 6.73 months, crawled at 6.68 
months and walked at 11.66 months. 
</P>
<P>
	They also found that the infants without walkers scored higher  
on the Bayley test of mental development given infants, scoring 
123.16 points, compared to 116.76 for those in see-feet walkers and 
113.15 for infants in sight-blocking walkers. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers concluded that ``restriction in a walker may  
exert its greatest influence on mental development during the 6- to 
9-month age period,'' a time regarded as transformational in a 
child's intellectual development., 
</P>
<P>
	But they also found that walker children tended to begin  
catching up to their no-walker contemporaries after they began 
crawling and were no longer confined to walkers. 
</P>
<P>
	Those in the see-feet walkers tended to catch up to the  
no-walker children by 9 months and those in sight-blocking walkers 
caught up to the other two groups by 12 months, they reported. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
