<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART's Montoya Watching Franchitti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SURFERS PARADISE, Australia (AP) -- It won't be a match race by  
any stretch, but Colombian rookie Juan Montoya will be keeping a 
special eye on Dario Franchitti in Sunday's Honda Gold Coast Indy 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	One race remains after the Australian event -- the Marlboro 500  
in Fontana, Calif., on Oct. 31 -- and Montoya has a 13-point lead 
over the Scotsman going into Sunday's race on the 2.795-mile 
temporary road course that winds among the high-rises in Surfers 
Paradise. 
</P>
<P>
	With only Franchitti a threat -- Canadian Paul Tracy is third  
with 155 points -- Montoya, who has 200 points on the year, will be 
hoping to finish ahead of Franchitti in the race. And that won't 
necessarily have to be in first. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know what to expect,'' Montoya said during the  
driver breakfast Thursday. ``Of course I want to go out there and 
win. If I win I get more points, but the important thing is winning 
the championship so we're going to try to do all we need to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya, 24, is bidding to become the first Indy-car rookie to  
win the CART title since Nigel Mansell in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-year-old Franchitti knows he will have to win or at the  
very least rely on a continuation of bad luck which prevented 
Montoya from winning the championship in the last race at Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya started from the pole in that race but a communication  
breakdown with his pit crew led to him clipping a car which had 
stopped at a tire wall after a full-course caution was declared. 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti finished second in that race in his Reynard-Honda  
behind his Team Kool Green teammate Tracy to give him 16 points and 
a chance for the championship. 
</P>
<P>
	On arriving on the Gold Coast this week, Franchitti said another  
1-2 finish for his team was on the agenda but this time with Tracy, 
who cannot win the championship, in the second position. 
</P>
<P>
	Team owner and expatriate Australian Barry Green has agreed,  
saying under the right conditions Tracy would probably give way to 
Franchitti. 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti, who has two victories, four seconds and four thirds  
this year, said the race was critical to his chances, as is winning 
the pole on the tight track. 
</P>
<P>
	``Victory is the race could go to any one of 10 drivers but I  
have to make sure at least I'm in the leading division,'' 
Franchitti said. ``Whatever happens I have to beat him (Montoya) to 
stay in contention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya came to the CART series after a five-year European  
apprenticeship. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year he won the European Formula 3000 championship and this  
year succeeded two-time Indy-car champion Alex Zanardi -- who went 
to Formula One -- with the Chip Ganassi Racing Team. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya has said he would like to try his luck in Formula One  
but for the moment he's content in the CART series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expected to win a couple of races but not to be leading,''  
he said. ``So far so good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifying sessions are set for Friday and Saturday before  
Sunday's 65-lap race. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
