<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks were higher Thursday morning as  
investors welcomed news of a possible merger between two large 
Japanese banks. The dollar rose against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 20.91 points,  
or 0.12 percent, to 17,775.40 at the end of the morning session. 
The average closed down 336.32 points, or 1.86 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded at 106.93 yen, up 0.35 yen from its level of  
106.58 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above 106.60 yen late 
Wednesday in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, Tokyo share prices rallied Thursday as  
investors hailed news of a potential huge bank merger between 
Sumitomo Bank and Sakura Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese banks said Thursday they are in talks toward a  
broad alliance that media reports said would create the world's 
second-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In separate statements, the banks said they were discussing a  
tie-up ``aimed at integration.'' But they added it was too early to 
announce a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	If finalized, the combination would create a financial giant  
with about $938.26 billion in total funds, second only to the 
entity formed by the planned merger of Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, Fuji 
Bank and Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd. Assets at those three banks 
exceed $1.2 trillion. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Sumitomo-Sakura news has rekindled hopes for industry  
realignments,'' said Hiroichi Nishi, deputy general manager at 
Nikko Securities Co. ``But weak New York markets are worrisome, and 
investor buying interests aren't spreading.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although financial stocks have gained strongly on the  
Sumitomo-Sakura news, the overall market was top-heavy after 
continued sharp falls in U.S. stocks, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average closed down  
184.90 points at 10,232.16 Wednesday, extending its drop of 231.12 
points Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 7.36 points, or 0.48 percent, to 1,534.32. The 
TOPIX closed down 15.84 points, or 1.03 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar rose on buying by Japanese trust  
banks and overseas securities houses, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although the yen gained earlier on the Sakura-Sumitomo bank  
tie-up news, trust names are repeating recent moves and buying back 
the dollar,'' says Shigeru Hashimoto, vice president of foreign 
exchange at Sanwa bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Wednesday, the greenback rallied after Japan's  
central bank announced it would begin purchasing short-term 
government bonds to make sure money keeps flowing through the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	That would increase the amount of yen in the market, and could  
help stem the Japanese currency's recent strength against the 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	But traders later expressed disappointment that the central bank  
failed to counter the yen's advance with a straight infusion of new 
money supply into the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities fear that too strong a yen could undermine Japan's  
rebound from its worst downturn in 50 years by making Japanese 
exports more expensive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was trading at 115.58 yen Thursday  
morning, above its level of 114.87 yen late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7650 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.7600 percent. Its 
price fell 0.05 point to 99.43. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
