<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 13, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan's Army Chief in Control  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Ousted Prime Minster Nawaz Sharif  
remained under house arrest today in Islamabad, Pakistan's capital, 
where troops loyal to army Chief Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf staged 
yesterday's coup. Musharraf showed no signs that he planned to 
relinquish power any time soon. The coup took place within an hour 
of Sharif's announcement that he had fired Musharraf as army chief. 
Pakistani citizens seemed unfazed: Many celebrated the ouster of a 
prime minister who had become increasingly unpopular because of a 
deteriorating economy and his ongoing power struggle with political 
opponents and the military. 

</P>
<P>
	Chechens: We're Ready To Fight  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Despite advances by Russian troops,  
Chechen fighters still hold strong positions and are prepared to 
rebuff Russian offensives, the leader of the rebel republic said in 
an interview published today. Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov 
said he was ``100 percent sure'' the conflict would end in peace 
talks. ``But thousands of soldiers will die first,'' Maskhadov 
predicted in an interview with the Russian newspaper Vremya MN. 
Chechnya has governed itself since 1996, when its gruesome two-year 
civil war with Russia ended. 

</P>
<P>
	Palestinians Object to Israeli Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BETHLEHEM, West Bank (AP) -- Palestinians are denouncing Israeli  
plans for a permanent border crossing between Jerusalem and the 
West Bank town of Bethlehem, saying it will limit travel by 
Palestinians and make the crossing more intimidating for them. The 
crossing currently is a makeshift checkpoint made of cement blocks 
and manned by a few Israeli soldiers. But Israeli officials plan a 
permanent structure to monitor a four-lane crossing. They say the 
new checkpoint is intended to deal with a surge in Christian 
tourists heading for Bethlehem for the new millennium. 

</P>
<P>
	Austria Leader: We're Not Neo-Nazis  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Defending Austria's image following the  
strong electoral showing of a far-right party, the chancellor 
insisted today his country is not a hotbed of neo-Nazi activities. 
Chancellor Viktor Klima spoke out after many countries, 
particularly Israel, denounced the stunning gains by Joerg Haider's 
anti-immigrant Freedom Party in Oct. 3 elections. ``Austria is 
certainly not a land that has slipped to the right margin by the 
election, nor is it a land of neo-Nazis,'' Klima told a news 
conference. ``Austria is a very solidified democracy.'' 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Assures S. Korea on No Gun Ri  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A senior U.S. official assured South  
Korea today that Washington will provide full cooperation in 
investigating allegations American soldiers killed hundreds of 
Korean refugees in the early days of the Korean War. Assistant U.S. 
Secretary of State Stanley Roth made the pledge in meetings with 
South Korean Foreign Minister Hong Soon-young and Defense Minister 
Cho Sung-tae. On Sept. 30, The Associated Press reported that 
American war veterans confirmed accounts by South Korean villagers 
who said they saw U.S. forces shoot civilians under a railroad 
bridge at No Gun Ri, South Korea, in July 1950. 

</P>
<P>
	Columbia Professor Wins Economics Nobel  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Robert A. Mundell of Columbia  
University, whose theories helped create a common currency for the 
European Union, won the Nobel Prize for economic sciences today for 
his analysis of exchange rates and how they affect monetary 
policies. The Canadian-born economist's work has made contributions 
far outside esoteric academic circles by clarifying how exchange 
rates fluctuate when a government shifts from a flexible to a fixed 
monetary policy. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Down 55.09  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today as  
Intel's disappointing earnings report hurt technology shares. In 
the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial 
average was down 55.09 at 10,361.97. Declines led advancers 
1,389-981. Just before the hour, the Nasdaq Composite Index was 
down 32.73 at 2,839.70. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Win Game One of NLCS  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Greg Maddux shut down Mike Piazza and the New  
York Mets for seven innings and John Rocker sprinted from the 
bullpen to finish them off, giving the Atlanta Braves a 4-2 victory 
last night in Game 1 of the NL Championship Series. Game 2 is this 
afternoon. The American League Championship Series starts tonight 
with the Boston Red Sox playing the Yankees in New York. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
