<HEADLINE> Top IOC Officials To Testify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Atlanta's Olympic bid will be under the  
microscope Thursday as the House Commerce Subcommittee on Oversight 
and Investigations begins hearings on bid practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Several high-profile Olympic officials, including IOC director  
general Francois Carrard and IOC vice president Anita DeFrantz, are 
expected to testify. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch has said he is willing to  
appear before the committee, but couldn't fit Thursday's hearing 
into his schedule and sent Carrard instead. He has said he may be 
able to testify during a meeting next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and former Sen. Howard  
Baker, both members of the IOC 2000 reform team, are expected to be 
at the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think (Thursday) will be an opportunity to get all the  
information that we've been collecting in the course of our 
investigation out on the table,'' said David Woodruff, spokesman 
for Rep. Fred Upton, the committee's chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodruff said Upton's investigation has focused primarily on  
Atlanta's bid for the 1996 Summer Olympics, and that will likely be 
the main topic of testimony Thursday, though Salt Lake City's bid 
for the 2002 Winter Games may be discussed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Salt Lake will be coming up,'' Woodruff said.  
``Certainly comparisons can be made, but our people ... are really 
focusing on Atlanta.'' 
  	   	
</P>
