<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Yen; Otherwise Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the Japanese yen on  
Wednesday after Japan's central bank announced steps that will 
increase the amount of yen on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 106.60  
Japanese yen, up from 106.31 on Tuesday, but well below Wednesday's 
early high of nearly 108 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was mixed against other major currencies, with the  
euro rising to $1.0794, up from $1.0758 late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rallied strongly against the yen early in the day  
after the Bank of Japan said it will begin purchasing short-term 
government bonds to make sure money keeps flowing through the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	After the early jump, however, traders expressed disappointment  
that the central bank failed to counter the yen's advance with a 
straight infusion of new money supply into the economy. A strong 
yen could undermine Japan's rebound from a recession by making 
Japanese exports more expensive in other currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, the dollar was quoted at 1.4734  
Swiss francs, down from 1.4806, and 1.4818 Canadian dollars, up 
from 1.4746. The British pound slipped to $1.6559 from Tuesday's 
quote of $1.6567. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8118 German 
marks, down from 1.8179; 6.0765 French francs, down from 6.0968; 
and 1,793.67 Italian lire, down from 1,799.67. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
