<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stocks closed mostly lower Wednesday,  
with the top markets dragged down by the overnight plunge on Wall 
Street and local financial concerns and only a few smaller markets 
rising. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell  
336.32 points, or 1.86 percent, to close at 17,754.49. The index 
had risen 28.63 points, or 0.16 percent, on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders attributed the fall in Tokyo to New York's decline and  
concerns that the Japanese central bank was not taking any actions 
firm enough to halt the Japanese yen's advance against the U.S. 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average closed Tuesday at 10,417.06,  
down 2.1 percent, or 231.12 points, its 10th biggest point drop in 
history and the steepest since May 27. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese market fell in response, with traders also worried  
about the yen's recent strength, which some analysts fear could 
stifle the economic recovery by making Japanese exports too 
expensive abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 106.58 yen  
late Wednesday in Tokyo, up 0.30 yen from late Tuesday and also 
above the overnight 106.31 yen level in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks plunged, triggered by Wall Street's losses and  
concerns over new share placements. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 2.2 percent, or 283.48  
points, to close at 12,475.87. That brought the Hang Seng's losses 
this week to 4.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow's fall hurt sentiment, and analysts also said a number  
of Hong Kong traders have been selling shares so they can have cash 
in hand for new offerings soon to hit the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore prices closed down as Wall Street's drop sidelined  
many investors. The benchmark Straits Times Index slipped 22.67 
points, or 1.1 percent, to 2,095.6. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stocks plummeted 2.46 percent as investors  
unloaded banking and finance stocks ahead of expected poor results. 
The Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell 9.86 points to 391.50. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares ended marginally higher, with the  
index edging into positive territory on late buying attributed to 
government intervention. The JSX Composite Index ended up 0.1 
percent, or 0.565 point, at 571.947. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares ended lower, as the fall on Wall  
Street spooked investors and confusion over the government's bank 
merger plan dampened sentiment. The benchmark Composite Index lost 
1.1 percent, or 8.29 points, to end at 737.28. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks fell on renewed concerns over a  
possible rise in U.S. interest rates that contributed to Wall 
Street's plunge. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index 
dropped 15.68 points, or 0.8 percent, to 2,050.72. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Taiwan shares closed virtually unchanged. The key  
Weighted Price Index finished up just 1.57 points at 7,836.94. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Prices closed marginally lower, after recovering from  
larger losses earlier in the day that were triggered by Wall 
Street's fall. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index shed 0.73 
point to end at 855.52. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares closed lower, despite a resilient  
resources sector and a late rally in gold stocks. The All 
Ordinaries Index finished at 2,906.7, down 27.4 points, or 0.9 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares closed higher, with the key index  
boosted by gains in market bellwether Telecom Corp. of New Zealand. 
The NZSE-40 capital index finished at 2,095.48, up 25.06 points, or 
1.2 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
