<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves Turn Starters Into Relievers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- For the third time in the postseason, Atlanta  
Braves manager Bobby Cox had a member of his magnificent starting 
rotation do double duty in the bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, it was John Smoltz coming on for the ninth inning  
in the first relief appearance of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know what was going on,'' said Smoltz, who had made  
379 major-league starts without ever pitching out of the bullpen. 
``I didn't know what to do -- walk in, run in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He compromised with a jog and did just fine in the unprecedented  
situation. Shawon Dunston grounded out, Roger Cedeno flied out, and 
pinch-hitter Bobby Bonilla was called out on strikes to end the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	In Game 3 of the division series, Cox used both Greg Maddux and  
Kevin Millwood during a crucial 5-3 victory over the Astros. 
Millwood picked up the first save of his career with a scoreless 
12th inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Against the Mets, Millwood was back in the familiar role of  
starter, allowing only two earned runs in 7 1-3 innings but leaving 
with the tying run at second. Cox called on his closer, John 
Rocker, to face New York's two most dangerous left-handed hitters, 
John Olerud and Robin Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy worked to perfection as Rocker struck out both,  
preserving Atlanta's one-run lead, before returning to the mound to 
begin the ninth. That was merely a ploy to force the Mets to send 
up the right-handed Dunston as a pinch-hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	As soon as Dunston's name was announced, Cox emerged from the  
dugout while the crowd booed. The reaction quickly turned to cheers 
when the fans noticed No. 29 coming in from the bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, I wanted to get the first hitter out,'' Smoltz  
said. ``I knew if I got the first hitter out, that would take care 
of my nerves. I knew that from all my experience with the role, 
which was none. Actually, I was looking at it like I was trying to 
close out a game as a starter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox said all of his starters have the mentality to work out of  
the bullpen. He took a plunge into that brave new world last year, 
using Maddux to save a victory in Game 5 of the NLCS. 
</P>
<P>
	Just two games into this year's championship series, Tom Glavine  
is the only starter who hasn't gotten a chance to pitch in relief. 
He is scheduled to start Game 3 at Shea Stadium on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to have a good makeup and you have to be kind of  
special,'' Cox said. ``I'm sure a lot of pitchers could do it, but 
these guys have pretty good stuff, too. You kind of want to get 
them in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe he should have considered this sooner. Throughout the  
decade, the Braves bullpen took much of the blame for the team 
winning only one World Series title despite making the postseason 
in every non-strike season since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Things go so bad, in fact, that Smoltz volunteered several years  
ago to go to the bullpen as the closer. Cox finally accepted the 
offer Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got an appreciation far greater than I ever had before  
for what those guys do,'' Smoltz said. ``It's funny. I've offered 
many times before to go in situations like this but it never 
happened.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991013.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 15:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vermeil: A Dinosaur Roars to Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Nobody's snickering at Dick Vermeil anymore.  
</P>
<P>
	The St. Louis Rams won all of nine games the first two years of  
his comeback, and Vermeil was dismissed as a coaching dinosaur. 
Now, with the Rams at 4-0 and the NFL's only unbeaten team, Vermeil 
is very much in vogue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the focal point and the figurehead of it right now,'' he  
said Wednesday. ``And it's fun. I mean, it's fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suddenly, everyone wants a piece of the 62-year-old coach. The  
interview requests keep coming. Monday night football nabbed him 
for a guest spot at halftime. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he gave everybody credit but himself,'' offensive  
guard Adam Timmerman said. ``And he definitely deserves some.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the NFL chose Vermeil for a national conference  
call -- the same day St. Louis Cardinals great Stan Musial visited 
the team. Vermeil will be on Fox's NFL pregame show before the Rams 
play at Atlanta on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I appreciate it, and it gives me a chance to present the Rams  
to the country,'' Vermeil said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vermeil's exposure rivals that of his previously unknown  
quarterback. Kurt Warner, the NFL's leading passer, on Tuesday 
turned down a request from David Letterman's show. This week, he's 
on the cover of Sports Illustrated. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good to see everybody get a little publicity,'' free  
safety Keith Lyle said. ``It's just fun. It's a good wave to ride 
for everybody right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before this season, most of the Rams' games were dogs of the  
week. After much fanfare in 1997, following a 14-year absence from 
coaching, Vermeil and an older staff that included four former NFL 
head coaches endured a 5-11 season. Last year was even worse, a 
4-12 finish that included an eight-game losing streak, and a 
winless record in the NFC West. 
</P>
<P>
	As this season began, the Rams had more losses in the 1990s than  
any other NFL team. The team and local TV stations bought up 
tickets to keep alive the team's streak of sellouts since moving 
from Anaheim, Calif., in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Rams are a hot ticket, and Vermeil can do no wrong.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great feeling,'' he said. ``It's a real tribute to some  
people that worked very, very hard. I'm not trying to say we are 
where we want to be, but I think we're on the right road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As best he can, Vermeil is trying to stay grounded. He usually  
says the right things about there being 12 games to go, and he 
hasn't forgotten the down days last year when the Rams dropped 
eight in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can be a mentally and physically tough team and ignore  
what we've done and only be concerned with what we have to do, I 
think we can continue experiencing success,'' Vermeil said. 
</P>
<P>
	But sometimes the giddiness shows. His news conference Wednesday  
was somewhat reminiscent of the day he was hired. There were 
references to Super Bowl successes and such friends as Bill Walsh, 
Broncos coach Mike Shanahan and Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get down,'' Vermeil said. ``The thing I've always fallen  
back on is my experience. I've done it before.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991013.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 13:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Sets Oct. 25 Announcement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Pat Buchanan  
is preparing to bolt his party and begin a quest for the Reform 
Party nomination Oct. 25, officials close to the conservative 
commentator said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, cautioned  
that Buchanan could still reverse course and stay out of the 
increasingly fractious third-party bid. They said they don't expect 
that to happen. 
</P>
<P>
	In the clearest signal yet of his intentions, Buchanan's  
campaign mailed invitations to supporters Wednesday inviting them 
to a ``major announcement'' Oct. 25 at a Falls Church, Va., hotel, 
the officials said. His advisers expect him to announce his Reform 
Party candidacy at that time, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's almost too far down the pike to get out now,'' said one  
of the officials. 
</P>
<P>
	However, spokeswoman Joanne Hansen said no final decision has  
been made. 
</P>
<P>
	Lagging in GOP polls, Buchanan says he believes the party's  
nomination battle is rigged in favor of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, 
who he says is too moderate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reform Party nominee would lay claim to almost $13 million  
in federal matching money. Party founder Ross Perot earned 19 
percent of the vote in 1992 and 8 percent in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans fear that a third-party run by Buchanan would siphon  
conservative votes from their nominee. He won the New Hampshire 
primary in 1996 and put a scare into then-President George Bush in 
the 1992 primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, however, would not be assured the nomination. A parade  
of celebrities and politicians are mentioned as potential 
candidates, including New York tycoon Donald Trump, Minnesota Gov. 
Jesse Ventura, former Connecticut Gov. Lowell Weicker, actress 
Cybill Shepherd, actor Warren Beatty and Perot himself. 
</P>
<P>
	A new CNN/USA Today/Gallup Poll shows limited support for the  
third-party alternatives. Buchanan had the backing of 9 percent of 
those surveyed in a three-way matchup with Bush and Vice President 
Al Gore, the Democratic front-runner. Trump had 10 percent in a 
similar three-way matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	The unfavorability ratings of Buchanan, Ventura and Trump have  
increased as speculation about their presidential bids drew more 
media attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump formed an exploratory committee last week, and says he  
would spend $30 million if he jumps in the race. Buchanan, who has 
had trouble raising money in the GOP race, could not match that 
total but has more political experience than Trump. He is said to 
be worried about Trump's financial resources. 
</P>
<P>
	The contest is already heated.  
</P>
<P>
	Trump consultant Roger Stone said Buchanan wants attention, not  
the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pat's advocation at this point is running for president. It's  
all he does,'' Stone said in a telephone interview. ``Trump will 
spend $30 million to get on the ballots in every state. I don't 
think Pat can do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trump himself has called Buchanan's views ``prehistoric.''  
Buchanan is a staunch, anti-abortion conservative who drew 
criticism for questioning whether Nazi Germany was a threat to 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, the party's highest ranking elected official, has ruled  
out a 2000 presidential campaign, though the speculation continues. 
He is urging Trump to seek the nomination, saying Buchanan is too 
conservative on social issues for the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan is drawing support from the Perot wing of the party.  
</P>
<P>
	``I say to Roger Stone, `Bring your candidate on.' It'll be  
another head on the wall,'' said Pat Choate, Perot's 1996 running 
mate. 
</P>
<P>
	Perot himself has not taken sides in the nomination fight and  
has not ruled out jumping in the fray himself. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials close to Buchanan say his meetings with advisers  
are filled with strategic and thematic discussions about the 
third-party bid. His sister and top adviser, Bay Buchanan, is 
exploring party rules and is already seeking to plant Buchanan 
backers in state party leadership posts. Buchanan and his advisers 
are discussing language Buchanan would use to explain his 
departure, though he has not yet formally begun writing the speech. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991013.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 09:11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks Mostly Lower; Dow Down 67.75 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today as Intel's  
disappointing earnings report hurt technology shares. Blue chip 
stocks extended Tuesday's steep decline. 
</P>
<P>
	In late morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 67.75 at 10,349.30. The Dow tumbled 231.12 Tuesday 
in its second-worst performance of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 10.29 at 1,302.75, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was down 29.99 at 2,842.44. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, often considered a bellwether stock for the technology  
sector, fell 3 13/16 to 72 7/8. The company, the world's largest 
manufacturer of semiconductors, said late Tuesday it earned 55 
cents a share in the quarter, 2 cents below analysts' forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	The results surprised many Wall Street investors who have come  
to expect Intel to meet or beat analyst forecasts. Traders said the 
report also fostered nervousness about the semiconductor industry, 
which may face production troubles in the coming months as Taiwan, 
a major producer of semiconductor parts, rebuilds from a recent 
earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies that comprise the S&AMP;P 500 are expected to post  
average profit growth of more than 19 percent in the third quarter, 
according to First Call/Thomson Financial. But with expectations 
soaring, analysts say the companies that miss Wall Street's 
forecasts are in line for harsh punishment from investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Shobin, technical analyst at Lehman Brothers, warned  
that unless investors can shake lingering nervousness about rising 
interest rates, earnings may be unable to drive stocks much higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wall Street is expecting phenomenal earnings, and that might  
already be priced into the market,'' he said. ``Right now, 
investors seem willing to ignore the good news and embrace the 
bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some bad news came from the bond market, where prices slipped  
again, pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.24 
percent, from 6.22 percent late Tuesday. Rising yields on bonds can 
lure investors away from stocks as they seek out securities 
offering fixed, guaranteed returns. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 12-to-7 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 251.6 million 
shares, slightly ahead of Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.33 to 422.35.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991013.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 09:11:00 </DATE_TIME>
