<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Farm Aid Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Highlights of the $8.7 billion farm assistance package:  
</P>
<P>
	--$5.5 billion to double the amount of money grain and cotton  
farmers will get through their ``market transition'' contracts with 
the government this year. 
</P>
<P>
	--$1.4 billion for weather-related losses, including $200 million  
for livestock producers. 
</P>
<P>
	--$475 million for payments to soybean and sunflower farmers.  
</P>
<P>
	--$400 million to reduce premiums for crop insurance next year.  
</P>
<P>
	--$328 million to compensate tobacco growers for declining  
cigarette sales. 
</P>
<P>
	--$200 million to subsidize sales of domestic cotton.  
</P>
<P>
	--$125 million for payments to dairy farmers.  
</P>
<P>
	--$42 million for payments to peanut producers.  
</P>
<P>
	--Suspends tax on sugar, saving producers about $40 milliona  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	--Raises payment limitations on crop subsidies so an individual  
farm could receive up to $300,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	--Extends dairy price supports through next year so government  
could continue buying surplus production. 
</P>
<P>
	--Meatpackers would be required to start reporting the prices  
they pay for cattle and hogs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
