<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dent To Officially Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- Three years after playing his last  
game, Richard Dent is going to retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Dent, the MVP of Super Bowl XX, will officially retire before  
the Chicago Bears' game Sunday against the Philadelphia Eagles. 
He'll serve as honorary captain for the game, and a banner with his 
No. 95 will fly at Soldier Field for the rest of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	A ferocious pass rusher, Dent set Bears records for sacks in a  
career (124.5), single season (17 1/2) and single game (4 1/2). He 
finished his career with a total of 137 1/2 sacks, fifth-best in NFL 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Dent was part of the ``46'' defense that led the Bears to a  
Super Bowl title in 1986. The New England Patriots were sacked a 
record seven times and held to just seven yards rushing in 
Chicago's 46-10 victory. Dent had 1 1/2 sacks and two forced fumbles 
to become only the fourth defensive player to earn MVP honors. 
</P>
<P>
	After 11 years in Chicago, Dent played for San Francisco in 1994  
and won his second Super Bowl ring. He returned to Chicago for the 
1995 season and played his last season with the Indianapolis Colts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
