<HEADLINE> Tribune Earnings Up 31 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Tribune Co., the parent of the Chicago Tribune  
and the Chicago Cubs, reported Wednesday that third quarter 
earnings jumped 31 percent from the same quarter in 1998 led by 
gains in its broadcasting unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Operating profits for the quarter grew to $109 million, or 40  
cents a share, from $83 million or 30 cents per share in the 1998 
third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The company exceeded analysts' expectations, pegged at 38 cents  
a share in a survey by First Call/Thomson Financial. Per-share 
results reflect a two-for-one common stock split, effective Sept. 
9. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-quarter revenue rose almost 11 percent to $836.7 million  
from $757.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribune reported gains in all three of its divisions:  
broadcasting and entertainment, publishing and education. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our broadcasting group again outperformed the industry,  
leading Tribune to a record third quarter. All of our business 
groups have contributed to a great year so far and are well 
positioned for solid long-term growth,'' said John W. Madigan, 
Tribune chairman, president and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcasting and entertainment operating profits were up 40  
percent to $97 million for the quarter. The company cited improved 
results surrounding its operation of the Cubs, which came in last 
place on the field, and at its television stations, particularly WB 
Network affiliates in New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tribune operates 18 television stations and four radio  
stations, as well as four newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	For the nine months ended Sept. 26, Tribune Co. reported  
revenues of $2.4 billion, up 9 percent from $2.2 billion in the 
year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding gains from the sales of subsidiaries and invesments  
and other special items, the company earned $299.2 million, or 
$1.11 a diluted share, compared with $253.9 million, or 91 cents a 
diluted share in the first nine months of 1998. The per-share 
figures reflect the stock split. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribune shares fell 43 3/4 cents Wednesday to $50.93 3/4 a share on  
the New York Stock Exchange. The company reported its earnings 
after the close of U.S. markets. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
