<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tech's Hamilton Emerges for Heisman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Chris Weinke for Heisman?  
</P>
<P>
	Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton may be the new favorite to win the  
Heisman Trophy now that Peter Warrick is all but out of the race 
following his suspension, but what about Weinke, Warrick's 
teammate? 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida State quarterback not only plays for the top-ranked  
team, but he directed the undefeated Seminoles to a 41-35 victory 
over Hamilton and the Yellow Jackets on Sept. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, Hamilton had a terrific game, throwing for 387 yards and  
four TDs, but Weinke was pretty good, too. The former minor league 
baseball player passed for 262 yards and three TDs -- and his team 
won. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton and Alabama's Shaun Alexander, along with Wisconsin's  
Ron Dayne and Purdue's Drew Brees, have picked up support now that 
Warrick faces legal problems following his arrest last week for 
felony grand theft. But Weinke stated his case quite nicely last 
Saturday, throwing for 332 yards and two TDs in leading the 
Seminoles over No. 24 Miami, 31-21. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could sense him taking over,'' Florida State coach Bobby  
Bowden said. ``I could sense that he thought, `I've got to do it. 
I've got to get it done.' It was unspoken. Some of the kids sensed 
it, too, that he was taking it into his hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Weinke: ``Coach Bowden challenged us with Pete out by  
saying that this was an opportunity for somebody else to make a 
name for themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weinke mentioned a few of his receivers, but it was Weinke who  
made the strongest statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton leads the nation in passing efficiency with 1,347 yards  
and 12 TDs (he also has 321 yards rushing and six TDs), while 
Weinke is seventh in passing with 1,627 yards and 13 TDs. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MISSISSIPPI MADNESS:* One Mississippi, two Mississippi, three  
Mississippi. ... 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time in the 63-year history of The Associated  
Press college football poll, the three major schools from the 
``Hospitality State'' are ranked in the Top 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi State, 6-0 for the first time in 55 years, checked  
in at No. 12 this week after its 18-16 victory over Auburn on 
Saturday. The Bulldogs moved into the poll on Sept. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Mississippi (5-1) and Southern Mississippi (3-2)  
slipped in, the Rebels at No. 22, the Golden Eagles at No. 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi moved out to its best start since 1990 with a 20-13  
victory over Tulane, and Southern Mississippi ended a 22-game 
losing streak against Top 25 teams with a 39-22 victory over East 
Carolina, which dropped from No. 16 to No. 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the three Mississippi schools was in the Top 25 in 1997,  
but not all at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ANOTHER POLL MILESTONE:* With No. 24 Miami (2-3) still in the  
Top 25 after three straight losses, the question is: When was the 
last time a losing team was ranked so deep in the season? 
</P>
<P>
	The answer: Southern California, in 1971. The Trojans were 3-4  
and ranked No. 24 after a 28-14 victory against No. 6 Notre Dame. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami, a 31-21 loser to No. 1 Florida State on Saturday, has  
lost three in a row for just the second time in 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	That streak should end on Saturday when the Hurricanes play host  
to Temple (1-5). 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LOW TECH:* Texas Tech doesn't have Ricky Williams to promote  
for the Heisman Trophy anymore, so the Red Raiders are trying to 
cash in on a goal post. 
</P>
<P>
	Tech is selling pieces of the mangled goal post toppled by fans  
after its 21-19 victory over Texas A&AMP;M on Oct. 2. Commemorative 
pieces of the only goal post ever torn down at Jones Stadium can be 
ordered by phone through the Double T Shoppe on campus for $25. A 
limited number of the souvenirs is expected to be sold at the store 
late next week. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *EXTRA POINTS:* Southern California (3-2), which attempts to  
extend its winning streak over Notre Dame (3-3) to four in a row on 
Saturday, had minus-20 yards in last week's 31-24 loss at Arizona. 
... Rutgers (0-5) is the only one of 114 I-A teams without an 
interception this season. How bad is Rutgers? In his fourth season, 
coach Terry Shea has a 3-20 Big East record; Temple coach Bobby 
Wallace is 3-6 in his second season. ... Could be that Kansas State 
RB Frank Murphy won't return this season after surgery on his 
sprained right ankle. Nobody knows for sure because coach Bill 
Snyder isn't saying much. ``We won't allow him to come back too 
fast,'' Snyder said. ``He'll move along at the speed that medical 
science and his body allow. We're not going to get ahead of 
things.'' ... Duke (1-4) ended a seven-game losing streak with last 
week's 24-17 OT victory over Virginia. Excited Lamar Grant said: 
``We still have bowl aspirations. We're 1-4 overall, but we're 1-1 
in the conference and we can still have a great finish in the 
conference. Easy big fellow, No. 8 Georgia Tech comes to town on 
Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
