<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> e-Scan Tracks Online Shoppers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Like to drink cola? You probably visit travel  
sites if you sit down regularly to surf the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Buy lots of dog food? Bet you browse ESPN.com or weather.com.  
</P>
<P>
	A cookie lover? Chances are you visit financial sites when  
you're on the Web, with maybe a stop at MTV.com along the way. 
</P>
<P>
	Two research firms armed with data showing just such consumer  
quirks presented a project Wednesday that they say gives companies 
an unprecedented ability to target just the right dot-coms with 
their ads. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint effort, e-Scan, tracks consumer behavior from click-on  
to the grocery checkout line, linking buyers' preferences with what 
Web sites they visit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a major stride forward in Internet measurement for  
consumer packaged goods firms,'' said Joe Durrett, chief executive 
officer of Chicago-based Information Resources Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	IRI's partner is New York-based Media Metrix, an online  
marketing research firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The project has been tracking the Internet usage and buying  
behavior of 3,000 households since July to learn how the two are 
connected. 
</P>
<P>
	Media Metrix collects Internet viewing data from software  
installed in computers that follows a surfer's clicks to determine 
the amount of time spent on a site and the time of day. 
</P>
<P>
	IRI tracks purchases made from grocery and convenience stores,  
enlisting shoppers to record them with the use of miniature 
scanning devices. 
</P>
<P>
	The two have brought their technologies together by installing  
Media Metrix software in the personal computers of IRI shoppers. 
</P>
<P>
	Early efforts have turned up some predictable results and some  
surprising ones. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, heavy purchasers of non-carbonated drinks --  
typically the young -- browse ty.com, the home of Beanie Babies, or 
nick.com, Nickelodeon's site. 
</P>
<P>
	But cookie consumers, who tend to be female more often than not,  
enjoy surfing Motley Fool's fool.com, a financial news site most 
often visited by men. Go figure. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Greenberg, president of IRI's e-commerce division, says the  
``revolutionary'' service marks the first time companies can link 
what people are doing on the Web with what they've been buying. 
</P>
<P>
	Procter &AMP; Gamble, which participated in the testing of e-Scan,  
says it will improve Internet marketing efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``This gives us the knowledge to reallocate resources to align  
brand products with specific interactive consumers.'' said Jon 
Mamela, the company's digital research manager. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
