<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cable Gains Boost Time Warner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner Inc. reported third-quarter net  
income of $360 million, bouncing back from a loss a year ago as big 
gains from cable TV offset weaker results in its music and 
television studios. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest media and entertainment company reported  
Wednesday its earnings were equivalent to 27 cents per share and 
compared to a loss of $37 million, or 3 cents a share, in the same 
period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 2 percent to $6.72 billion from $6.59 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner's third-quarter profits were lifted by one-time  
gains from the sale and exchange of cable systems, a process cable 
providers use to concentrate their subscribers in specific 
geographic areas. But even without those gains, the company's 
pre-tax cash flow -- a measurement widely used by financial analysts 
-- rose by 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings were in line with Wall Street expectations. Time  
Warner's stock started higher but was down $1.81 1/4 at $61.50 as 
prices fell overall on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner's stock has been sliding from about $77 since  
mid-July, when the co-chairmen of the Warner Bros. music and movie 
studio resigned abruptly. The stock took another hit this summer 
after a prominent analyst cautioned that Time Warner's music 
earnings would be lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from its cable systems, Time Warner also posted stronger  
results in its large magazine publishing division, Time Inc., and 
its cable networks division, which includes CNN, HBO and Cinemax. 
Time Inc. has been reaping benefits from two successful magazine 
launches, Teen People and InStyle. 
</P>
<P>
	The main signs of weakness during the quarter were in the music  
division, where results were off at Time Warner's half-owned 
Columbia House direct sales business, and in movie and TV 
production, where earnings a year ago were pumped up by syndicated 
sales of ``Seinfeld.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite an overall decline in its filmed entertainment division,  
Time Warner well at the box office this summer with the ``Austin 
Powers'' sequel in the United States and with the releases of ``The 
Matrix'' and ``Wild Wild West'' overseas. ``The Matrix'' also had 
big sales in the new DVD format in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner chairman Gerald Levin said that despite the decline  
in music earnings this quarter he expected profits to turn up 
modestly next year, when the company plans new releases from 
Madonna, Tracy Chapman and others. ``This year, we didn't have a 
lot of the major acts we had before,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner also posted a wider loss at its growing WB network,  
which is entering its sixth season. The network is doing well with 
young viewers with shows like ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' but 
Time Warner blamed the larger loss on steeper costs for programming 
and expanding the number of stations that carry WB. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, Time Warner earned $1.06  
billion, or 81 cents a share, compared to a loss of $158 million, 
or 13 cents a share, in the same period a year earlier. Revenues 
rose 2 percent to $19.35 billion from $18.98 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-month figures for this year were inflated by the cable  
deals as well as a one-time gain from the early termination of a 
long-term video distribution agreement with MGM/UA. 
</P>
<P>
	With 13 million subscribers, Time Warner is the nation's  
second-largest cable provider after AT&AMP;T Corp. In September, Time 
Warner launched its jointly owned Road Runner hi-speed cable 
Internet access service in New York City and eight other markets, 
bringing its subscriber base to 420,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Time Warner floated shares in its year-old phone service  
subsidiary, Time Warner Telecom. Like other major cable companies, 
Time Warner is hoping to use its cable TV lines to deliver phone 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the first quarter that Time Warner reported fully  
consolidated results from its Time Warner Entertainment subsidiary, 
which holds many of its movie, TV and cable assets. The cable 
provider MediaOne, which holds a 25 percent stake in the 
subsidiary, ceded management rights over its interest to Time 
Warner in August. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, which is in the process of acquiring MediaOne, has been  
negotiating with Time Warner over how to restructure the ownership 
of the TWE unit. Time Warner and AT&AMP;T have already agreed to 
cooperate on providing phone service over Time Warner's cable 
lines, a process AT&AMP;T has undertaken with its many new cable 
properties. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
