<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Customs Targets Intellectual Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Customs Service is creating a center aimed  
at cracking down on the theft of motion pictures, computer 
software, music and other illegally pirated intellectual property. 
</P>
<P>
	Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly made the announcement  
Wednesday and is part of his agency's ongoing efforts to combat the 
growing piracy problem in this area. 
</P>
<P>
	The center, which will open within 30 days, will coordinate the  
efforts of roughly 15 agencies now involved in investigating and 
prosecuting cases that involve pirated intellectual property, such 
as films, software and music, that are illegally copied. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main objectives ... will be to eliminate duplication of  
investigative efforts between agencies and to coordinate 
multinational investigations,'' Kelly said. 
</P>
<P>
	Four current customs officials and four current FBI officials  
are expected to work at the center at customs headquarters, said 
Customs Service spokesman Dean Boyd. 
</P>
<P>
	From fiscal year 1994 through 1998, the value of intellectual  
property rights seizures increased to nearly $76 million from $37 
million, customs said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the same period, the number of seizures also increased to  
3,409 from 2,203. Last year, offenders in China and Taiwan 
accounted for nearly half of all the pirated merchandise seized, 
the agency said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
