<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Priceline.com Sues Microsoft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Priceline.com filed a federal lawsuit  
Wednesday against Microsoft Corp. and its Expedia Inc. subsidiary, 
claiming that a new online hotel pricing service by Expedia.com 
violates Priceline's patent. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit also alleges that Microsoft is in violation of the  
Connecticut Unfair Trade Practices Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Priceline.com is seeking monetary damages, and an order shutting  
down the Expedia service, said Evan R. Chesler, Priceline's 
attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't seen the complaint yet, so we aren't in the  
position to comment in detail. But we are confident that when all 
the facts are on the table, Microsoft's position will prevail,'' 
said Tom Pilla, Microsoft spokesman. ``We respect the intellectual 
property of other companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both services allow a customer to log onto a Web site and book a  
hotel room by answering a series of questions, including how much 
the customer is willing to pay for the room. 
</P>
<P>
	Priceline.com implemented its hotel service in September, 1998,  
a year before Expedia implemented its service, said Chesler. 
</P>
<P>
	A patent for Priceline's name-your-own-price service was issued  
on Aug. 11, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft showed an interest in the Priceline service and  
representatives from the two companies met in November to discuss a 
proposal for ``co-marketing arrangements,'' the lawsuit claims. But 
after Priceline provided Microsoft with confidential information, 
the discussions ended without an agreement, according to the 
complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	During a corporate conference in July, Microsoft chairman Bill  
Gates told Priceline officials he would not let a patent stand in 
his way, the lawsuit claims. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
