<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Boxer Dies After KO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuelan super bantamweight boxer  
Carlos Barreto died from head injuries received during a bout in 
which he was knocked out, his mother said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Barreto, 23, an interim World Boxing Association champion, was  
knocked out last Saturday in the 10th round by fellow Venezuelan 
Jose Luis Valbuena in a match for the Latin American super 
bantamweight title. 
</P>
<P>
	Barreto staggered to his corner after a blow from Valbuena,  
became unconscious and fell into a coma. He died Tuesday night 
after efforts by doctors to bring him out of the coma failed, his 
mother, Nora de Barreto, told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	De Barreto said her son had been rushed to a public hospital in  
Caracas, but couldn't be treated because of a lack of functioning 
equipment. He was taken to another hospital, but had to wait three 
hours for treatment while the hospital confirmed that the family 
had enough money to pay for treatment, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Valbuena said the boxers had been friends for several years and  
often trained together. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to need a psychologist to be able to live with this  
weight on my shoulders,'' Valbuena said Wednesday, tears dripping 
from his eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	Barreto had most recently been ranked No. 5 by the WBA. He had  
fought professionally since 1996, with a 9-3-1 record including 
nine knockouts. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the interim WBA champion in his weight category from  
October to November 1998, temporarily holding the title while 
Mexico's Enrique Sanchez recovered from an injury. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
