<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ETrade Reports Smaller Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) -- ETrade Group Inc. reported a  
smaller-than-expected fourth-quarter loss Wednesday as it added 
310,000 customers in three months. 
</P>
<P>
	For the period ending Sept. 30, the nation's second-largest  
Internet brokerage behind Charles Schwab reported a loss of $26.7 
million, or 11 cents a share, compared to a loss of $15.2 million, 
or 8 cents a share for the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street had expected ETrade to lose 13 cents a share,  
according to a survey of analysts by First Call/Thomson Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	The company attributed the loss to the costs of building up its  
infrastructure and customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	ETrade ended the quarter with 1.55 million accounts, up from  
1.24 million accounts in the previous quarter. It was managing 
customer assets of $28 billion, up from $26 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The brokerage said it spent $79.3 million, or $238 per account,  
in the fourth quarter to gain new customers, many of whom were 
smaller investors shunned by rival online brokerages. Company 
executives said that strategy will position it well for the future 
as those investors make more money and invest more. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said revenue fell 2 percent from the previous  
quarter to $173.2 million, as it cut prices on some active traders' 
transactions in August to $4.95 from $14.95. Customer trades were 
little changed at about 80,350 daily, compared with about 80,600 
the previous quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	ETrade executives said the company also will benefit from its  
pending acquisition of online bank Telebanc Financial for $1.6 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	For the full fiscal year, ETrade lost $54.7 million, or 23 cents  
per share, compared to earnings of $1.69 million, or 1 cent per 
share, in the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues came to $621.4 million, up from $335.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	ETrade shares rose 21 7/8 cents to $25.62 1/2 in trading on the  
Nadaq stock market. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
