<HEADLINE> Grains Lower; Soybeans Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures inched higher Wednesday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade as investors closely eyed the drought in 
Brazil. Grain futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans climbed as much as 7 cents a bushel before closing with  
a minimal gain for the day, barely extending their rally of the 
previous two days. 
</P>
<P>
	A long dry spell in key growing regions in Brazil has the market  
nervous about negative repercussions during planting season. 
Forecasts predict light weekend rains in parts of that country. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn prices fell based on increasing expectations of a strong  
harvest. The U.S. Agriculture Department estimated Tuesday 
estimated that the harvest was 43 percent complete as of Sunday, 
compared with the average 28 percent for that stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat was pressured by concerns over the status of agricultural  
credits to Pakistan, where a military coup took place on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 2 1/4 cents to $2.55 1/4 per bushel;  
December corn fell 3/4 cent to $2.00 1/2 per bushel; December oats fell 
1/4 cent to $1.09 per bushel; November soybeans rose 1/4 cent to $4.99 1/4 
per bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle fell .95 cent to 69.27 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .20 cent to 80.82 cents a pound; 
December lean hogs rose .82 cent to 47.57 cents a pound; February 
frozen pork bellies fell 1.40 cents to 62.80 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
