<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AL Playoffs: Ribs, Arms and Rivalry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While Red Sox fans look at history and get  
scared, the New York Yankees look at this Boston team and worry. 
</P>
<P>
	They worry about all those runs the Red Sox scored against  
Cleveland, 
</P>
<P>
	They worry about facing Pedro Martinez.  
</P>
<P>
	They worry their traditional rival might finally trip them up.  
</P>
<P>
	``They ought to be playing the Jets or somebody, the way they're  
scoring,'' said Paul O'Neill, who plans to play tonight, fractured 
rib and all. 
</P>
<P>
	The AL Championship Series begins at Yankee Stadium with Orlando  
``El Duque'' Hernandez pitching for the World Series champions 
against Kent Mercker. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, Kent Mercker.  
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I was getting to start by default,'' said Mercker,  
chased by Cleveland after 1 2-3 innings in Game 4 Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Sox fans assume the worst, especially against the Yankees.  
They remember how Thurman Munson and Reggie Jackson kept Carlton 
Fisk and the great Boston teams of the late 1970s out of the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the '70s, there was some hatred among the players: Munson  
didn't like Fisk, Fisk didn't like Munson, the Yankees didn't like 
Bill Lee,'' said Yankees coach Don Zimmer, who managed those Boston 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not there anymore,'' Zimmer said Tuesday. ``I hate to  
use the word, but there is some hatred between the two clubs. The 
way I'm reading the papers now, there may be some between the Mets 
and Atlanta.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many New York players didn't think Boston would make the  
playoffs, and few thought the Red Sox would overcome Cleveland, 
especially after losing the first two games. 
</P>
<P>
	``They take advantage of whatever weakness they may happen to  
spy on any particular day,'' New York manager Joe Torre said. ``I 
was one of them that thought Toronto was going to pass them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston was 8-4 against New York this year, one of only three  
teams to win the season series. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have a good lineup,'' New York shortstop Derek Jeter  
said. ``They have a team that scraps for runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the Yankees' compliments, Boston said New York is a  
clear favorite to go win its third AL pennant in four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a source of motivation to try to prove everybody wrong.  
It is obvious we are an underdog,'' Mercker said. ``We were an 
underdog against Cleveland, but as long as 25 guys and five coaches 
in that clubhouse don't believe that, there is no situation -- you 
are down five runs early, everyone thinks we are supposed to be 
down five runs, so what do we got to lose?'' 
</P>
<P>
	As is usual, the Yankees seemed more concerned about themselves  
than their opponent, convinced that if they play to their 
potential, they can't be beat. After all, they've won 10 straight 
postseason games. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Yankees swept Texas in the first round, holding the  
Rangers to a grand total of one run for the second straight year, 
the Red Sox lost the first two games against Cleveland, then won 
three straight, 9-3, 23-7 and 12-8. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston outscored Cleveland 47-32. But here's the bad news for  
the Red Sox: Excluding the 10 shutout innings by Pedro Martinez, 
Boston had a 7.83 team ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, 3-0 with a 0.41 in three career postseason starts,  
was 2-1 with a 2.70 ERA against Boston during the regular season 
after going 1-0 versus the Red Sox last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes no difference if you beat a team up in the regular  
season or they beat you up,'' Jeter said. ``It's a whole different 
intensity level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking of intensity, O'Neill is baseball's most prominent  
example. When it's the postseason, no Gatorade jug or water cooler 
is safe when he strikes out. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, he learned that he has a fractured rib from an Oct. 2  
collision with a fence in foul territory at Tampa Bay, and the 
Yankees worried whether he would be able to play. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill, who sat out Saturday's first-round clincher at Texas,  
took about two dozens swings during batting practice Tuesday and 
more in a cage underneath the stands at Yankee Stadium, then 
pronounced himself ready. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless I wake up tomorrow and have a big setback, then  
everything is go at this point,'' said O'Neill, who hit .298 with 
six RBIs against Boston this year. ``If we were an hour from the 
game right now, I am pretty sure that Joe would have me in the 
lineup.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* David Cone, who didn't pitch in the first round because of  
New York's sweep, will start Game 2 Thursday against Ramon 
Martinez. Roger Clemens starts Game 3 Saturday against Pedro 
Martinez at Fenway Park, and Andy Pettitte starts Game 4 Sunday 
against Bret Saberhagen. ... Boston cut RHP Tim Wakefield and RHP 
John Wasdin from its active roster and added RHP Bryce Florie and 
RHP Pat Rapp. ... New York's two candidates to replace O'Neill both 
struggled against the Red Sox. Shane Spencer was 2-for-18 and Ricky 
Ledee 1-for-8. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
