<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hughes Electronics Posts Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- Hughes Electronics Corp. lost $29.6  
million in the third quarter, mainly because of expenses from its 
acquisition of two satellite-TV rivals and higher satellite costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss for the quarter that ended Sept. 30 amounted to 13  
cents a share, and compared with a $42.9 million profit, or 11 
cents a share, in the same period a year ago, Hughes reported 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The General Motors subsidiary, whose operations include the  
nation's biggest satellite-television service, had revenues of 
$1.99 billion, up from $1.51 billion in the same quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes said much of the loss resulted from its recent purchase  
of Primestar and United States Satellite Broadcasting, which merged 
with the company's DirecTV satellite-TV business. The number of 
DirecTV subscribers rose to 7.7 million in the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Aided by the acquisitions, DirecTV's revenues increased to $1.05  
billion, up from $408 million in the third quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had the best quarter ever for new DirecTV subscriber  
additions in the United States,'' said Michael Smith, Hughes 
chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for Hughes' satellite systems dropped to $510.8  
million, down from $688.9 million in the same period last year. 
Higher capital expenses in Hughes' satellite services division 
contributed to the quarterly loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest expenses also contributed to the loss.  
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, Hughes lost $43.6  
million, or 17 cents a share, compared with a $143.5 million, or 36 
cents per share, profit for the same time in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine-month revenues came to $5.22 billion, up from $4.17  
billion. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
