<HEADLINE> Dale Evans Admitted to Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) -- Western movie legend Dale Evans was in  
serious but stable condition today after having her pacemaker 
replaced. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans, 86, underwent the procedure Tuesday evening at Loma Linda  
University Medical Center, hospital spokeswoman Anita Rockwell 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tests show she may have suffered a mild heart attack, said her  
grandson, Dustin Rogers. He said she is feisty and eager to leave 
the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's doing real well,'' he said. ``Her spirits are really  
high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evans was admitted to Desert Valley Hospital on Monday and  
transferred Tuesday to be closer to her cardiologist, Rogers said. 
She suffered a stroke in 1996 and a heart attack in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans' illness may have been prompted by a diet change and  
exhaustion from attending a Lone Pine film festival last weekend, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans starred in 35 movies and a 1950s television series with  
her husband Roy Rogers and co-wrote his theme song ``Happy Trails 
to You.'' She has also written dozens of inspirational books and 
hosts a cable television talk show on the Trinity Broadcast 
Network. 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband died in 1998 from congestive heart failure at 86.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
