<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Web Health Cos. Seek Ethics Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Leading Internet health companies said Wednesday  
they want to avert government regulation by developing their own 
standards for content, sponsorship and privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	C. Everett Koop, the former surgeon general who owns part of  
drkoop.com, joined representatives from about a dozen Web firms to 
begin hammering out an ethics policy. Although no agreement was 
reached, participants said Tuesday night's meeting among fierce 
competitors was a milestone. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that you can have a group of industry leaders get  
together to talk about the problems is significant,'' said Joel A. 
Kahn, chief medical officer for the InteliHealth site, a joint 
venture between Aetna U.S. Healthcare and Johns Hopkins University. 
</P>
<P>
	The question now, he said, is where the group heads.  
Participants set no timetable and made no decisions on how broad or 
how focused the guidelines should be. 
</P>
<P>
	George Lundberg, editor in chief for the Medscape information  
site, said the group may draw on existing standards for medical 
journals, businesses and publishers. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry wants to demonstrate that it could police itself,  
Lundberg said. He was fired as editor of the Journal of the 
American Medical Association for publishing a survey on sexual 
attitudes that coincided with President Clinton's impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanie Fulton, a spokeswoman for drkoop.com, said Koop  
convened and facilitated the meeting because he felt the industry 
needed to address ethics. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Web sites, including Koop's, have come under criticism for  
failing to fully disclose sponsorship. For a time, Koop was 
entitled to a commission on products sold through his Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics also say that sites containing misleading information  
ultimately harm patients and the rest of the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Intel Corp. and the American Medical Association  
addressed concerns about privacy by announcing ways to verify 
online the identities of doctors and patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Helga Rippen, chairwoman for the Internet Healthcare Coalition,  
may seek to include participants from academia and other sectors. 
Her coalition plans a summit in February to draft guidelines. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
