<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms moved into portions of New York this  
morning and clouds increased over the rest of the Northeast. Rain 
fell in the western Great Lakes, northern Plains and Southeast, 
while mostly clear skies prevailed over much of the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Later today, a cold front was expected to trigger scattered  
showers and thunderstorms over the Northeast, eastern Great Lakes, 
and mid-Atlantic States. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the storms were forecast to be severe across the eastern  
Great Lakes, likely with wind gusts of up to 60 mph and hail up to 
an inch in diameter. Wind gusts of over 30 mph could be expected in 
other areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms also were forecast to develop over parts of the  
Southeast, especially over the Carolinas, where several rivers 
continue above flood stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Partly cloudy skies and mostly dry, breezy weather was expected  
in the central and southern Plains. A few showers, however, were 
possible over extreme southern Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Another cold front will be responsible for light showers in  
Washington, northern Oregon, northern Idaho, and extreme 
northwestern Montana. Dry conditions were expected over the rest of 
the Rockies and West. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's forecast highs: In the 60s and 70s in the Northeast and  
the northern Plains; in the 60s in the Pacific Northwest; in the 
70s and 80s in the Southeast; and in the 90s and 100s in the 
Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature Tuesday in the continental United States  
was 106 degrees in Gila Bend, Ariz. The lowest temperature was 23 
degrees in Truckee, Calif. 
</P>
</TEXT>
