<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hirshorn Museum Marks Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton picked an exhibit of  
work by French sculptor Auguste Rodin and his American followers to 
celebrate the 25th anniversary of the Hirshhorn Museum, the part of 
the Smithsonian Institution devoted to modern art. 
</P>
<P>
	She spoke to a small group of Hirshhorn devotees Tuesday in the  
sculpture garden she created, a section of the White House grounds 
favored by first lady Jacqueline Kennedy. Exhibits of modern 
carving there have been one of Mrs. Clinton's favorite projects. 
She spoke in front of a gigantic bronze of Rodin's ``The Thinker'' 
and facing another of his works, ``The Three Shades.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What you're seeing now is our seventh show, which spotlights  
the influence that Rodin has had on 20th century American 
sculpture,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hirshhorn has contributed to many of these shows.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton told of President Lyndon Johnson's bid to Joseph H.  
Hirshhorn, a Latvian-born American financier, to donate his huge 
collection for a new national museum, which was built next to the 
popular Air and Space Museum. It opened to the public on Oct. 4, 
1974, one of the world's largest collections of modern art, with 
more than 6,500 paintings and sculptures. 
</P>
<P>
	``He insisted that it be free, because he know that the arts are  
central, not peripheral, to our lives,'' she said. ``I know he 
would be pleased by the role that the arts played in everything 
from the development revolution to the revitalization of poetry and 
cinema in so much of the former Soviet Union.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
