<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 13, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Senate Rejects Nuke Test Ban  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today rejected a landmark treaty to  
ban nuclear testing by a vote of 48-51, much to the chagrin of 
President Clinton. As expected, the final vote closely followed 
party lines, with only four Republicans voting for the treaty. 
Democrats vowed to make the rejection a prime 2000 campaign issue, 
claiming polls show most Americans favor such a ban. Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., called the pact ``fatally 
flawed.'' 

</P>
<P>
	No Charges in JonBenet Case  
</P>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- After a 13-month investigation, a grand  
jury decided there was insufficient evidence to indict anyone in 
the JonBenet Ramsey slaying, District Attorney Alex Hunter 
announced today. The crime had set off a long, controversial search 
for her killer. The prominence of the 6-year-old girl's family -- 
the father the millionaire president of Access Graphics, the mother 
a former Miss West Virginia -- and the beauty contest background of 
the young victim brought worldwide attention to the case for nearly 
three years. 

</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris Admits Tobacco Dangers  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Philip Morris Tobacco Cos, Inc., is  
acknowledging publicly that tobacco isn't safe. The company, in an 
effort to remake its corporate image, has launched a corporate Web 
site stating ``there is no 'safe' cigarette'' and that ``cigarette 
smoking is addictive, as that term is most commonly used today.'' 
Philip Morris, which for years disputed research that found smoking 
contributed to medical problems, also acknowledged that smokers 
face tremendous health hazards. 

</P>
<P>
	AFL-CIO Endorses Gore  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Al Gore received a powerful endorsement today  
from the AFL-CIO, calling him ``a supporter of working families and 
a champion of our unions.'' In a resolution at the close of its 
biennial convention, the AFL-CIO chose between the two Democrats 
running for president: ``While one candidate, Bill Bradley, has the 
respect of many and a good record, there is no question that Al 
Gore is the favorite.'' Gore said, ``It's been a good week.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Buchanan Plans 'Major Announcement'  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Officials close to Pat Buchanan said today he  
is planning to bolt the GOP on Oct. 25 to seek the Reform Party's 
presidential nomination. Two officials warned that Buchanan may 
still change his mind, but they don't expect that to happen. 
Buchanan's campaign mailed invitations to supporters for a ``major 
announcement'' at a Falls Church, Va., hotel. 

</P>
<P>
	Priceline.com Sues Microsoft  
</P>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Priceline.com filed a federal lawsuit  
Wednesday against Microsoft Corp. and its Expedia Inc. subsidiary, 
claiming that a new online hotel pricing service by Expedia.com 
violates Priceline's patent. The lawsuit also alleges that 
Microsoft is in violation of the Connecticut Unfair Trade Practices 
Act. Priceline.com is seeking monetary damages, and an order 
shutting down the Expedia service, said Evan R. Chesler, 
Priceline's attorney. 

</P>
<P>
	Wireless Stock Trading Coming Soon  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Users of the new mobile phones with wireless  
Internet access will be able to trade stocks for the first time 
through a new service from Sprint PCS and Ameritrade Holding. Later 
this month, Ameritrade customers will be able to access their 
accounts, place trades and receive stock alerts through the 
recently introduced Sprint PCS Wireless Web service. Many online 
brokers have already introduced beepers and other wireless devices 
for investors to manage their accounts, but the service announced 
today is the first to be deployed on the new breed of wireless 
Internet phones that are now hitting the market. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise on Merger News  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks advanced Thursday as investors  
welcomed news of a possible merger between two large Japanese 
banks. The Nikkei rose 11.26 to 17,765.75 in early trading. In New 
York, the Dow industrials fell 184.90 at 10,232.16. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Beat Mets, Lead NLCS 2-0  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Braves beat the Mets 4-3 this afternoon, and  
lead the best-of-7 National League Championship Series 2-0. 
Atlanta's Eddie Perez and Brian Jordan both hit two-run homers in 
the sixth inning to clinch the victory. The Braves brought in John 
Smoltz for the first relief appearance of his major league career 
to cap the game. He pitched a perfect ninth inning for a save. 

</P>
<P>
	Yzerman Moves Up NHL Scoring List  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Detroit's Steve Yzerman moved into a tie for  
eighth place on the NHL career scoring list as the Red Wings beat 
the St. Louis Blues 4-2 tonight. Yzerman's assist on Igor 
Larionov's tiebreaking goal in the second period was his 1,487th 
career point, tying him with former teammate Paul Coffey for eighth 
place. Mario Lemieux is seventh at 1,494. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
