<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newman Visits Sick Kids in Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Paul Newman gave thanks to Ireland's  
prime minister after visiting a center for sick children set up by 
the actor's charity foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	Newman, 74, said he was grateful that Prime Minister Bertie  
Ahern provided the Barretstown Castle estate as a location for the 
Hole in the Wall Gang Camp, which has played host to nearly 4,000 
children from 20 European countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Children from Ireland and all over Europe come to this  
beautiful place, to live and play with others who understand what 
it means to battle against illness and be like children again,'' 
Newman said Wednesday. ``They leave the Barretstown Gang Camp with 
a fresh outlook on life and a renewed strength of spirit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newman started the Hole in the Wall foundation in 1988 and has  
several camps in the United States. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
