<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Gets States' Rights Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court seemed ready Wednesday to  
shield states against federal lawsuits by employees who say they 
are victims of age bias. 
</P>
<P>
	Hearing arguments in three related cases from Florida and  
Alabama, the justices appeared headed toward ruling that a federal 
anti-bias law, the Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967, 
cannot trump states' 11th Amendment immunity against being sued in 
federal courts. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's decision will be announced by late June.  
</P>
<P>
	In a series of 5-4 rulings in recent years, the court ignited a  
states' rights revolution by sapping the federal government's power 
over states. Nothing in Wednesday's 60-minute courtroom session 
indicated any shift among the justices. 
</P>
<P>
	More difficult to predict is whether the justices will use the  
three ADEA cases to dramatically curtail Congress' power to attack 
various forms of discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	Several justices, in questions and comments from the bench,  
suggested Congress can enforce the 14th Amendment's 
equal-protection guarantee only when seeking to protect people 
discriminated against because of race, national origin, religion 
and perhaps gender. 
</P>
<P>
	If the court ruled in line with those comments, that could  
undermine -- or even invalidate -- federal laws banning public and 
private discrimination based on age and physical disabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	In previous decisions, the court has deemed race, national  
origin and religion as specially protected categories. Laws or 
government practices that treat people differently for those 
reasons are the hardest to defend. 
</P>
<P>
	Differing government treatment based on someone's sex is also  
vulnerable to court challenges, but not as vulnerable. Differing 
treatment based on other factors -- such as age or disabilities -- is 
most often allowed by courts -- unless found to be based on 
irrational ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court ruled in the Florida and Alabama cases  
that the ADEA cannot be invoked in federal lawsuits against states 
and state agencies, in part because Congress did not specifically 
nullify states' immunity. 
</P>
<P>
	``This statute does not mention the 11th Amendment,'' Justice  
Sandra Day O'Connor said about the ADEA. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, referring to the 1974 amendment that  
extended the law to cover public employers, said Congress spent 
little time considering the states' immunity question. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress did not have the debate we are having here,'' he  
said. ``It didn't come close to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor and Kennedy have joined Chief Justice William H.  
Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas in 
cutting back congressional power while enhancing states' authority. 
</P>
<P>
	In each of those previous cases, Justices John Paul Stevens,  
David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer were 
dissenters. 
</P>
<P>
	Representing state workers, lawyer Jeremiah Collins argued that  
Congress intended to wipe out state employers' immunity against 
federal lawsuits even if it did not specifically say so. He said 
Congress addressed ``a pervasive problem in our society of how 
people look at older workers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration lawyer Barbara Underwood also urged the  
court to allow federal court access for ADEA claims against state 
employers. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jeffrey Sutton, representing the state employers, said  
Congress never had any indication they were engaged in ``pervasive 
and systematic discrimination'' -- a showing needed before Congress 
can invoke its remedial powers. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the three disputes, 36 current and former faculty  
members and librarians at Florida State University and Florida 
International University sued the state board of regents in federal 
court, contending that age bias was why they lost out on certain 
salary increases given to young faculty members. 
</P>
<P>
	In another, two associate professors at the state-run University  
of Montevallo in Alabama alleged that they had been wronged because 
younger faculty members were treated more favorably when it came to 
salaries and promotions. 
</P>
<P>
	And in a third, Florida prison guard Wellington Dickson said he  
lost out on a promotion because of discrimination based on, among 
other factors, his age. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
