<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House, Senate Near Land Bill Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate Republicans neared a deal  
Wednesday on a $14.3 billion bill financing land and cultural 
programs, but a veto by President Clinton seemed likely because of 
provisions helping oil and mining companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide only about one-third of the $800 million  
Clinton proposed to buy park land for the federal and state 
governments. Overall, it falls about $800 million short of what the 
president sought for the Interior Department and other agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	In a tentative agreement, the bill would let oil companies  
drilling on public lands avoid paying higher royalties to the 
government for up to six more months while a congressional study of 
the issue is completed. The higher payments have been delayed for 
two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Many hard-rock mining companies now using federal lands would be  
exempted from an Interior Department ruling limiting the size of 
their waste dumps to five acres. 
</P>
<P>
	Both provisions were less favorable to industry than earlier  
versions, but environmental groups complained they went too far. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is merely another delay tactic,'' Gawain Kripke of  
Friends of the Earth said of the oil royalty language. 
</P>
<P>
	Visiting the George Washington National Forest in Virginia to  
describe administration plans to preserve federal forests, Clinton 
accused GOP leaders of ``polluting our spending bills with special 
interest'' provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me be clear,'' he said. ``If the Interior bill lands on my  
desk looking like it does now, I will give it a good environmental 
response. I will send it straight back to the recycling bin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton spoke before the House-Senate bargainers finished their  
work. But White House spokesman Barry Toiv said that based on what 
was known about the House-Senate deal, ``They have not addressed 
all the concerns raised by the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,  
said the bill was ``almost signable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, just five of the 13 annual bills for fiscal 2000, which  
began Oct. 1, have been signed. Underlining his desire to avoid a 
big budget fight with Clinton, he urged his colleagues to finish 
their work so lawmakers can ``go home and start a new millennium 
next year without being here until Christmas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the few loose ends in the Interior bill was a  
House-Senate dispute over how much to provide for the National 
Endowment for the Arts. The House was holding out for $5 million 
less than the $103 million the Senate prefers. Clinton asked for 
$150 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill contains money for several projects that appear in  
neither the House or Senate versions of the bill, including: 
</P>
<P>
	--$22 million to help Alaskan communities where lumber plants are  
closing, won by Stevens. 
</P>
<P>
	--$39 million to prop up a financially ailing fund that finances  
health care for more than 60,000 retired mine workers, won by Sen. 
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
