<DOCNO> APW19991013.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Proposes New Mutual Fund Rules / Mutual Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New rules giving independent directors of  
mutual fund companies more power are being proposed by federal 
securities regulators, in an effort to better protect the millions 
of Americans who invest in the funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission voted Wednesday, 4-0, to  
seek public comment on the proposed rules, which include a 
requirement that the boards of most mutual fund companies have a 
majority of independent directors. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current rules, less than a majority -- 40 percent -- of fund  
companies' directors must be independent of the company, though 
most large fund companies voluntarily have a majority of 
independent directors. 
</P>
<P>
	Independent fund directors, who come from diverse backgrounds,  
are watchdogs responsible for protecting investors' interests and 
maintaining the funds' integrity. Their duties include overseeing 
mutual fund fees, monitoring financial performance and preventing 
conflicts of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a few small fund companies would be exempt from the  
regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Independent directors play an important role in keeping the  
mutual fund industry remarkably free of scandals, SEC officials 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	They ``serve as an investor's front-line defense against  
conflicts of interest and other potential abuses,'' SEC Chairman 
Arthur Levitt said before the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related move this summer, the SEC tightened its rules  
governing personal trading by mutual fund managers and employees. 
The stricter rules are designed to avoid conflicts of interest that 
can arise when fund managers and employees buy and sell securities 
for their own accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes by the market watchdog agency came in the wake of  
several cases of mutual fund managers being accused of improperly 
enriching themselves with investors' money. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Levitt has pushed the mutual fund industry for  
improved disclosure of fund fees and investment risks. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 83 million Americans now invest in mutual funds, whose  
total assets are estimated at $6 trillion, up from around $1 
trillion in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthew Fink, president of the Investment Company Institute, the  
industry's trade group, welcomed the latest SEC proposals, saying 
they ``are directed at further strengthening the effectiveness of 
independent mutual fund directors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the group endorsed a series of voluntary  
``best practices'' for the mutual fund industry, which it said went 
beyond what is required by law and regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other new rules proposed Wednesday by the SEC, which  
were opened to a 90-day public comment period: 
</P>
<P>
	--New independent directors of mutual fund companies must be  
nominated by current independent directors rather than fund company 
managers or investment advisers. 
</P>
<P>
	--Attorneys for independent directors must themselves be  
independent, not representing fund company management or close 
affiliates. 
</P>
<P>
	--Fund companies must disclose basic information about directors,  
as well as information that may raise conflict-of-interest 
concerns. They also must disclose directors' ownership of shares in 
the company's group of funds, to help investors assess whether the 
directors' interests are aligned with their own. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
