<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Miss Player Has Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Southern Mississippi baseball player  
Michael Artman, who set a school record with 106 hits this year, 
will miss the 2000 season while battling testicular cancer, 
according to baseball coach Corky Palmer. 
</P>
<P>
	Artman was diagnosed with testicular cancer in July and has  
undergone four sessions of chemotherapy. Palmer said Wednesday that 
doctors found a spot remaining in his abdomen that must be removed 
surgically. 
</P>
<P>
	Artman, a first baseman and center fielder, is scheduled for  
November surgery in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctors say the treatment has gone pretty well,'' Palmer  
said in a statement. ``His (hormone) count had gone down to a much 
lower level from when the doctors first picked up that he had 
cancer. They say it's not unusual to have to go back and remove a 
couple of spots after chemotherapy. We just want Michael to beat 
this thing and apparently he is doing that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Testicular cancer is treatable when detected in the early  
stages. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyclist Lance Armstrong, the 1993 world road race champion, won  
Tour de France this month after learning in October 1996 that he 
had testicular cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Artman, who batted .408 and finished the 1999 season with a  
20-game hitting streak, was diagnosed with cancer when he came home 
to Jackson on a break from playing summer baseball in Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	The 21-year-old junior helped lead Southern Mississippi to a  
40-23 record and its first NCAA Tournament appearance since 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
