<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Discuss Science and Morals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Looking ahead to a day when one's health  
future could be known at birth and an interplanetary Internet 
system may orbit the heavens, President Clinton and the first lady 
hosted a discussion of the moral and practical questions raised by 
emerging sciences. 
</P>
<P>
	Some questions raised during the eighth Millennium Evening at  
the White House, which focused on genetic research and information 
technology, were more puzzling than others: 
</P>
<P>
	``Do I really want a mouse smart enough to go to Princeton?''  
Clinton quipped. ``Won't it be sad to have an Internet connection 
with Mars if there's no Martians to write to?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Tuesday night event in the East Room, one of a series  
tackling weighty issues for the new millennium, dealt mostly with 
more serious matters, including how scientific advances have 
stimulated progress in the fields of health care, commerce and 
education while raising questions about privacy and intellectual 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the discussion were Clinton and first lady Hillary  
Rodham Clinton and guests Vinton Cerf, a creator of the Internet, 
and Eric Lander, a professor of biomedical research and director of 
the Whitehead Institute/Massachusetts Institute of Technology 
Center for Genome Research. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton used the evening to renew his calls for closing the  
technology gap between rich and poor Americans and public 
investment in scientific research. He also spoke in favor of 
protecting privacy at a time when science is looking ever deeper 
into human traits. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been working on this,'' he said. ``It's very important  
to me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
