<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Studies Small Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Today's small business is profitable and  
optimistic about staying that way, though it usually operates 
without any formal business plan, provides little or no benefits to 
employees and still primarily depends upon word of mouth to sell 
products and services. 
</P>
<P>
	At least that's the general profile that emerges from a  
comprehensive new survey conducted over the summer by The Willard &AMP; 
Shullman Group (WSG) in Greenwich, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	The market research firm questioned 525 small business owners --  
each of whom employs fewer than 500 workers -- on everything from 
profits and financing to what concerns keep them burning the 
midnight oil. 
</P>
<P>
	WSG said it conducted the survey to help its large-business  
clients, including many Fortune 500 companies, increase their sales 
to small businesses by better understanding them. The result: a 
more intimate look at one of the most important, and least 
understood, sectors of the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Small business as an aggregate employs half of the workers in  
the United States and produces half of the GDP (Gross Domestic 
Product), yet for some reason none of us knows anything about 
them,'' Robert Shullman, president of the WSG, said in a recent 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole small business market in America is just materially  
misunderstood,'' he added. ``The small company is probably more 
successful in figuring out how to sell to the big company than the 
other way around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, there's a good explanation for this lack of  
knowledge: There are roughly 10 million small businesses operating 
in this country, and their attitudes and behaviors are just as 
diverse as the products and services they sell and the regions 
where they sell them. And trying to learn more about them can be 
difficult since many of them are far from technologically savvy, a 
fact born out in the WSG survey. 
</P>
<P>
	Case and point: Only one in seven of those surveyed considered  
their firms to be technologically advanced, while one in four saw 
themselves as behind the times. Twenty-eight percent reported that 
they currently weren't using the Internet in their business, while 
14 percent said they still had no immediate plans to go online in 
the new millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	The technology most widely used by small businesses was the fax  
machine, with 82 percent saying they regularly depended on it in 
their operations. Seventy-one percent routinely used cell phones 
and personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty-four percent said they used the Internet for obtaining  
business information, while 45 percent reported that they used the 
Internet to communicate with others. By the year 2001, however, 54 
percent planned to use Internet applications for advertising and 
promotion, 41 percent to sell products or services, and 38 percent 
to find suppliers and make purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	So, what's the primary sales and marketing channel used by most  
of them right now? Word of mouth and referrals. 
</P>
<P>
	Ninety-one percent reported conducting business that way, and 61  
percent said it was their most successful channel. Nineteen percent 
said the Web was their most successful sales and marketing channel. 
</P>
<P>
	``With all the sophisticated technology today, the fact that  
'word of mouth' is still the most significant way of marketing, 
that blew me away,'' said Shullman. 
</P>
<P>
	Shullman says other results of the survey were equally as  
surprising. Less than half, or 41 percent, actually had an annual 
business plan, annual budget or long-range business plan in 
writing. The rest approached business planning by the ``seat of 
their pants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some results were more predictable.  
</P>
<P>
	Small business owners primarily looked to their own personal  
resources for capital. The predominant sources of their financing 
are: themselves, 41 percent; cash advances from personal credit 
cards, 36 percent; and personal lines of credit, 25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty-two percent of all business owners reported being  
profitable in 1998, while 26 percent lost money. Sixty-four percent 
anticipated growth and expansion in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	A quarter of those surveyed said they offered no benefits to  
their employees. 
</P>
<P>
	So what keeps small business owners up late at night? The top  
eight concerns were: operating expenses, cash flow, profitability, 
revenue, government regulations, pricing of products or services, 
hiring qualified staff, and size of their customer or client base. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 4.2 percentage  
points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
