<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 15:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palmer Set for Reunion With Jaguars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- Mark Brunell credits Chris Palmer with fixing  
his mechanics and making him a better quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer shaped Jacksonville's high-scoring offense and kept the  
Jaguars loose with practical jokes in the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	And now that he's gone, the Jaguars must miss their former  
offensive coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	Not the case, Browns coach Chris Palmer said.  
</P>
<P>
	``He was easy to replace,'' Palmer said. ``They didn't even hire  
a guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer, of course, was talking about himself. Following last  
season, his second as an assistant in Jacksonville, Palmer left for 
Cleveland and his first head coaching job with the expansion 
Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	And this week, Palmer, who has kept his dry sense of humor as  
the losses have piled up in Cleveland, returns to Jacksonville as 
the winless Browns play the Jaguars. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the second time this year Palmer will face an  
opponent he knows firsthand. Last month, when the Browns played New 
England, Palmer was torn as he coached against players he worked 
with for four years as an assistant with the Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer is looking forward to the challenge, but says these  
reunion games take an emotional toll. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always tough when you play against someone you know,''  
Palmer said. ``It's hard because you know the coaches and you know 
the players. The New England game was very difficult for me. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you have a relationship with players, it's tough to  
go back and compete against them. You spent two years with a team 
where you put your heart and soul and everything into it, and now 
you're trying to tear it down. It's always difficult to go back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And after reviewing game film of the Jaguars (4-1), Palmer said  
there is another disadvantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can also make you not sleep all week, too,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Jacksonville has been a coaching pipeline the past few years as  
first Kevin Gilbride, then Palmer and defensive coordinator Dick 
Jauron left Tom Coughlin's staff for top jobs elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	When Jauron departed for Chicago, he was replaced by Dom Capers.  
Under Capers, the Jaguars' defense has flourished and enters this 
Sunday as the top-ranked unit in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	After interviewing several candidates, Coughlin decided not  
replace Palmer, electing instead to run the offense himself this 
year, calling the plays for the first time since he was at Boston 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacksonville's offense may be suffering for it. Brunell's stats  
are way down -- three TDs and four interceptions -- and the Jaguars' 
are ranked just 14th in the league in total offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Could Palmer's loss have had something to do with the dropoff?  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think so,'' Coughlin said. ``I don't think that's been  
the circumstance. You have to move forward. It had always been in 
the back of my mind to see if I could go back and assume a little 
more responsibility. When Chris left I did interview some people 
but I did not feel like that was the direction we were going to go 
in. I just thought that this was best for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brunell, whose strained relationship with Coughlin has been a  
hot topic in Jacksonville this season, said he misses Palmer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris Palmer was one of the best quarterback coaches I ever  
had,'' Brunell said. ``He helped me with every aspect of my game. 
My mechanics, my reads. He worked on my fundamentals. He's just a 
great guy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We miss him like we'd miss any great coach that has gone on.  
He was great to have, not only as a coach, but as a person. And we 
certainly have a lot less practical jokes going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brunell and Palmer are good friends, who occasionally like to  
have some fun at the other's expense. 
</P>
<P>
	During summer training camp, Brunell had a special note shipped  
overnight to Palmer, the contents of which the Browns coach said 
were personal. 
</P>
<P>
	``He got me good,'' Palmer said. ``He knows when he can take his  
shots. I owe him one.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
