<DOCNO> APW19991013.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *Carlos Barreto    	
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Bantamweight boxer Carlos Barreto died  
from head injuries Tuesday, four days after he was knocked out 
during a bout, his mother said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barreto, 23, an interim World Boxing Association champion, fell  
into a coma Saturday after he was hit by fellow Venezuelan Jose 
Luis Valbuena in the 10th round of a match for the Latin American 
super bantamweight title. 
</P>
<P>
	He died Tuesday night, his mother, Nora de Barreto told The  
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Barreto was ranked No. 5 by the WBA. He had a 9-3-1 record with  
nine knockouts as a professional boxer since 1996. 

</P>
<P>
                          *David A. Huffman    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) -- David A. Huffman, who turned his  
college term paper into a computer coding procedure still in use 
four decades later, died of cancer Thursday. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Huffman developed the Huffman Coding Procedure, a mathematical  
technique still vital to data storage and transmission. The 
procedure assigns strings of 0's and 1's to each character in a 
file. 
</P>
<P>
	The codes are used to manage files in large computer systems;  
compress text, image and audio files; and compress data for 
transmission by fax machines, modems and high-definition television 
broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
	Huffman created the system while a graduate student in the 1950s  
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 

</P>
<P>
                          *J. Franklin Hyde    	
</P>
<P>
	CORNING, N.Y. (AP) -- J. Franklin Hyde, an organic chemist whose  
glass-making method made the fiber-optics revolution possible, died 
Monday. He was 96. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde's pioneering work with ultra-pure glass at Corning Glass  
Works in 1934 was used in radar during World War II. It didn't gain 
wide use until the 1960s when it led to durable spaceship windows, 
galaxy-gazing telescopes, precision lenses to build computer chips 
and signal-carrying optical fibers. 
</P>
<P>
	Optical fiber is now Corning Inc.'s biggest business.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm surprised at some of the things it has gone into, but I'm  
not surprised at the versatility of such a beautiful and useful 
material,'' Hyde said in an interview with The Associated Press 
last November. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Raymond Nichols    	
</P>
<P>
	LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- Raymond Nichols, a former chancellor of  
the University of Kansas, died Tuesday of natural causes. He was 
95. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols, a 1926 University of Kansas graduate, joined the  
university staff in 1929. He worked for the university for 44 
years, serving as executive secretary to the chancellor, executive 
secretary to the university, and then chancellor in 1972. He 
retired in 1973. 

</P>
<P>
                       *James Elliott Williams    	
</P>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- James Elliott Williams, one of the  
nation's most decorated war heroes, died Wednesday in a Florence 
hospital. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, a 20-year Navy veteran, earned three Purple Hearts,  
three Bronze Stars, the Vietnamese Cross of Gallantry, the Navy and 
Marine Corps Medal, two Silver Stars, the Navy Cross and the Medal 
of Honor. He was a boatswain's mate commanding patrol boats along 
the Mekong River during the Vietnam war. 
</P>
<P>
	He retired from the Navy in 1967 as a Petty Officer 1st Class  
and was appointed U.S. marshal for South Carolina, his home state. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton said in a statement Wednesday: ``Hillary and I  
are saddened to learn of the death of James Williams. His 
extraordinary bravery in combat and his dedicated service on behalf 
of this country were truly admirable.'' 

</P>
<P>
                            *Marvin Wood    	
</P>
<P>
	SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Marvin Wood, the high school coach whose  
tiny Indiana basketball team inspired the movie ``Hoosiers,'' died 
Wednesday of bone cancer. He was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood led Milan High School's march to the 1954 state  
championship, and was portrayed by Gene Hackman in the 1987 film 
about the underdogs' victory. His record at Milan was 52-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood was elected to the Indiana Basketball Hall of Fame in 1971.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
