<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fendi Sells To Prada, Louis Vuitton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a consolidation of luxury goods makers, the  
Fendi family is selling control in the fashion house known for 
``baguette'' handbags and extravagent fur coats by designer Karl 
Lagerfeld to a joint venture of Prada SpA and LVMH Moet Hennessy 
Louis Vuitton SA. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal were not disclosed in the announcement  
Tuesday, but a person familiar with the deal said the 51 percent 
interest in Fendi was sold for about $900 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement ended a bidding contest for the Italian company.  
The Fendi family rejected lower bids by Gucci and Texas Pacific 
Group, a U.S. investment firm. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see Fendi as, if you wish, a company that was like Prada or  
Gucci five years ago,'' said Bernard Arnault, chairman of 
French-based LVMH. ``There is a very high potential for growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LVMH plans to expand the number of Fendi stores worldwide, while  
Italy's Prada will focus on improving Fendi's purchasing and 
manufacturing operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a perfect fit,'' said Kurt Barnard, president of  
Barnard's Retail Trend Report, an industry newsletter. ``They 
apparently are planning to put money into this venture; it's going 
to go great guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rome-based design house was founded in 1925 by Edoardo and  
Adele Fendi, and has been owned by their five daughters since the 
1980s. Today, Fendi is one of the most chic names on the catwalks, 
and sales of its eyeglasses, perfume, clothing, shoes and watches 
are expected to hit $490 million this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fendi sisters will retain a 49 percent interest, and the  
family will continue to hold key executive positions, president, 
general manager, and head of product development. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale of Fendi is just the latest in a frenzy of deals that  
are realigning the trendsetters in fashion. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Prada purchased Jil Sander and Helmut Lang.  
Gucci was acquired by Pinault-Printemps-Redoute, and Valentino was 
snapped up by HdP. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Calvin Klein put himself on the sale rack. The New  
York designer hired an investment bank to look for a buyer or 
strategic partner to expand his product line and open new stores. 
</P>
<P>
	``People revere the name Fendi, Calvin Klein, Moet &AMP; Chandon,  
but while they revere it they seem to be buying less of it,'' 
Barnard said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, increased competition is forcing luxury  
companies to become more efficient. And that often means finding a 
partner. 
</P>
<P>
	LVMH has been an aggressive buyer. The company makes Hennessy  
cognac, Moet &AMP; Chandon champagnes, and the Louis Vuitton luggage. 
In the fashion world, LVMH owns the Celine, Givenchy and Kenzo 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnault, the chairman, recently lost a bidding war for Gucci,  
but came back to beat Gucci in the contest for Fendi -- which may be 
his last for a while. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not need to buy any brands, we have a plan to double our  
size in five years with our existing properties,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
