<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clemens Is Armed for Fenway Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When he set his pitching rotation for the  
American League championship series, Yankees manager Joe Torre knew 
immediately what that meant: 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Clemens pitching Game 3 against Pedro Martinez in Fenway  
Park -- the hero of Fenway past facing the hero of Fenway present. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a lot of fun,'' said Torre, who appreciates  
such moments. ``Obviously -- what Roger has meant to that 
organization and that ballpark for a number of years and, of 
course, what Pedro has done this year. Pitching in the shadows, if 
the sun is out, it ought to be interesting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens was the cornerstone of the Red Sox staff for 11 years,  
winning 192 games and three Cy Young Awards, twice striking out a 
record 20 batters in a game. When he left Boston as a free agent, 
he scooped some dirt from the Fenway mound, a keepsake for the 
power pitcher who had become a New England icon. 
</P>
<P>
	After two more Cy Young awards in Toronto, he was traded to New  
York this season. With his longtime uniform No. 21 already being 
worn by right fielder Paul O'Neill, Clemens reversed the digits and 
wore No. 12. Then in July, he switched to No. 22, the number his 
son, Koby, wore in Little League. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of all the emotional baggage, Torre avoided exposing  
Clemens to the Red Sox at Fenway on the Yankees' first visit to 
Boston in May. He did start there on July 31, allowing four runs in 
five innings and getting no decision in a 6-5 Yankees loss. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox beat him 4-1 on Sept. 12 at Yankee Stadium, part of  
a three-game Boston sweep and a so-so 14-10 season for his first 
year in New York. The loss left him with a 3-1 lifetime record 
against his old team. 
</P>
<P>
	If there were any demons left, he said they've been exorcised.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been removed from that situation for so many years,''  
Clemens said. ``If it was one year later, the situation would be 
different. But I've faced them so many times and I've been back at 
Fenway so many times. I know the mound, the wall. I'm familiar with 
the territory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens saw nothing out of the ordinary about the Yankees'  
rotation in which Orlando Hernandez started the opener against the 
Red Sox on Wednesday night with David Cone working Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever my slot is, I'll be there,'' he said. ``We've all got  
to pitch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre said the rotation fell into place after Clemens pitched  
the final game of the Yankees' first-round playoff sweep in Texas. 
He worked seven innings, allowing just three hits in a 3-0 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roger couldn't pitch Game 1 because he just pitched,'' the  
manager said. ``David has to pitch Game 2. So that pretty much fell 
into place for us the way we needed it to fall into place. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roger never hesitated when he found out he was the Game 3  
starter. I think after the last outing, he is anxious to get the 
ball again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Clemens' part, pitching in the playoffs in Texas, where he  
grew up, was every bit as emotional as will be Saturday's game in 
Boston, where he became a star. 
</P>
<P>
	``You catch your wind from the situation in Texas, and here you  
go again,'' he said. ``You collect your thoughts and here you go. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure it will be as loud as Texas. I don't expect any  
difference. There will be as much action in the stands as on the 
field. It should be fun for everyone involved.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
