<HEADLINE> Belgrade Holds World Sporting Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In the first international sports  
event since the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia, Fita Bayissa of 
Ethiopia won the Belgrade Race Through History on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bayissa finished the 6-kilometer race in 17 minutes, 8 seconds,  
for a one-second victory over Kenya's Paul Tergat, the five-time 
cross-country world champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``My race with Tergat was a matter of mental battle and I was  
stronger,'' said Bayissa, third in the 1992 Barcelona Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks as if this is one race I will never win, but I would  
love to run it again,'' Tergat said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morocco's Abderrahim Gourni was third in 17:12.  
</P>
<P>
	Because of the international isolation of Yugoslavia, which is  
trying to recover from NATO's air strikes, only 19 athletes from 15 
countries, including three Yugoslavs, negotiated the steep tracks 
inside Belgrade's ancient Kalemegdan fortress. Dragoslav Prpa was 
the top Yugoslav runner, finishing 10th. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers had to resolve numerous transportation problems  
because all participants had to be bused from neighboring Hungary. 
Bayissa also had difficulties with Hungarian immigration 
authorities, but the organizers ironed them out. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the international pressure on autocratic President  
Slobodan Milosevic, the European Union imposed a ban on air traffic 
with Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why should the runners suffer, why should the organizers  
suffer,'' Tergat said. ``I've always thought that athletics and 
sport should be about bringing people together.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
