<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chief Senate sponsors of campaign finance  
legislation signaled grudging willingness Tuesday to accept an 
increase in Watergate-era contribution limits as part of a broader 
effort to reduce the influence of money in politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John McCain, R-Ariz., said he would support an increase as  
``part of a package that would assure that other fundamental 
changes were made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., said he would be ``rather  
conservative in raising the limits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain and Feingold are co-sponsors of legislation to ban ``soft  
money'' contributions, the large, unregulated donations by 
corporations, unions and others to political parties. ``Hard 
money'' contributions are limited in amount by federal regulations 
and are given directly to individual candidates for office. 
</P>
<P>
	Hard money limits have been unchanged since they were enacted  
into law in the 1970s, and Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., is expected to 
propose an increase when campaign finance legislation reaches the 
Senate floor as early as Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hagel's proposal would raise limits to adjust for inflation over  
the last quarter-century. That would allow an individual to donate 
$3,000 to a candidate per election, up from the current $1,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to defeat a threatened filibuster, McCain and Feingold  
have introduced a pared-back campaign finance bill for debate that 
includes the soft money ban and a provision to give nonunion 
workers the ability to prevent unions from using their compulsory 
dues money for political purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	It does not include restrictions on advertisements that attack  
candidates but escape regulation because they are presented as 
``issue ads'' not covered by existing election law. Nor will it 
include a requirement for disclosure of campaign finance reports on 
the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Prospects for passage are uncertain.  
</P>
<P>
	In an indication of the complicated crosscurrents surrounding  
the bill, Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., announced his support for the 
bill during the day, but made clear he would oppose any effort to 
reattach the limits on ``issue ads.'' He also said he wanted a more 
stringent provision relating to nonunion workers and dues money. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, no friend of federal minimum  
wage legislation, conceded Tuesday that legislation for an increase 
is likely to reach the House floor either this year or next. 
</P>
<P>
	Armey, R-Texas, said Republicans will draft accompanying  
legislation designed to offset the damage he said an increase would 
inflict on low-wage earners, a reference to a package of tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	While many of those cuts will be aimed at small businesses, GOP  
leaders are also looking at a reduction in the estate tax. Asked 
how that could help a worker at minimum wage, Armey replied, ``I am 
not sure I can make that connection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, ``But again, that doesn't bother me a whole lot,  
since, you know, I mean we're talking here whose demagoguery trumps 
whose demagoguery. ... Let us throw mine in here, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did I say that? Hey, I've been here for 15 years. It's taken  
me 15 years to understand that in this racket you should demagogue 
without shame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	After testing the waters for a Senate campaign, Rep. David  
Minge, D-Minn., has decided to seek re-election to his House seat. 
Minge made his announcement over the weekend in Minnesota, where he 
became the latest Democrat to pass up a run for another office in 
hopes his party could gain a House majority in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Minge will be favored for re-election to a fifth House term. His  
retirement could have opened the doors to a major GOP effort to win 
the seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Minge's decision comes at a time when Democrats are still  
recruiting candidates to oppose Minnesota's first-term GOP Sen. Rod 
Grams, viewed by party strategists as vulnerable to a challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Minneapolis physician Steven Miles, former U.S. Attorney David  
Lillehaug and former Minneapolis alderman Dick Franson are in the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Cerisi, a trial lawyer, is expected to announce his  
decision to enter the race on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, former Rep. Tim Penny has indicated renewed  
interest in challenging Grams as a Democrat. Penny has close ties 
with Gov. Jesse Ventura, who is a member of the Reform Party, and 
had recently flirted with running for the Senate on that party's 
ticket. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
