<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pure-Glass Pioneer Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CORNING, N.Y. (AP) -- J. Franklin Hyde, an organic chemist who  
unlocked a method for making ultra-pure glass that eventually set 
in motion the fiber-optic revolution in telecommunications, is dead 
at age 96. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde's pioneering work in a Corning Glass Works laboratory in  
1934 lay mostly dormant until he was closing in on retirement in 
the 1960s. His discovery found myriad uses -- in durable spaceship 
windows, galaxy-gazing telescopes, precision lenses to build 
computer chips and signal-carrying optical fiber. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm surprised at some of the things it has gone into, but I'm  
not surprised at the versatility of such a beautiful and useful 
material,'' Hyde said in an interview with The Associated Press in 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde died Monday at his home on Marco Island, off Florida's  
southwest coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The impurity-free glass he found a practical way of making in  
bulk is called fused silica. It remains the most immaculate 
commercial glass available. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 19th century, scientists had tried melting quartz  
crystals to make fused silica, but that required heat in excess of 
1,725 degrees Centigrade, which was prohibitive. Besides, the 
molten glass couldn't easily be cooled into shapes. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde attacked the puzzle from an unconventional angle: He heated  
the basic raw materials -- sources of silicon and oxygen -- by 
running a volatile gas called silicon tetrachloride through an 
oxygen flame. 
</P>
<P>
	The ultra-pure vapors formed a fine, glassy powder of silicon  
dioxide that, he said, ``could be pressed into a shape just like 
clay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde's vapor-to-solid method is known as frame hydrolysis. That  
concept has since been broadened to build all kinds of 
high-performance materials an atom and a molecule at a time. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde, who grew up in Solvay near Syracuse, earned a doctorate in  
chemistry at the University of Illinois, completed a two-year 
fellowship at Harvard and was hired in 1930 by the materials 
supplier in western New York now known as Corning Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent more than two years working on the fused-silica  
project. But after winning his patent, he moved on to other 
projects. 
</P>
<P>
	His method found its first real-life use in a type of radar for  
detecting Japanese warships during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the glass serves as a key conduit in the semiconductor  
industry. Microlithographic ``stepper'' lenses made of fused silica 
provide the high transmission critical to miniaturizing computer 
chips. 
</P>
<P>
	In fiber optics, laser beams can travel for miles through  
fused-silica glass fibers without dissipating or scattering. Three 
Corning scientists invented optical fiber in the early 1970s, and 
fiber-optics technology is rapidly replacing copper as the backbone 
of America's telephone, cable television and computer networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Optical fiber is now Corning Inc.'s biggest business -- the  
company produces more than a third of the world's supply. But fused 
silica is manufactured by many companies worldwide, its sales 
running into billions of dollars a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde's wife of 61 years, Hildegard, died in 1991. He is survived  
by his three children, James, Ann and Sylvia. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991013.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 15:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
