<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 07:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hidden Fault Behind Near-Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two jumbo jets almost collided over China this  
year because of malfunctions in a system designed to prevent such 
airborne accidents. The near-collision prompted manufacturers to 
warn airlines around the world to make safety checks. 
</P>
<P>
	The alerts came from the leading aircraft makers, Boeing and  
Airbus Industrie, and are about to be followed with another from 
Allied Signal, which owns the company that made the faulty device. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied Signal said it never heard of the problem before and  
knows of no other aircraft at risk, although it is awaiting results 
of the safety checks it will recommend in the next two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal, which reported the problem Tuesday  
after reviewing an internal British Airways report, said as many as 
3,000 Boeing 747s, 727s, 737s and Airbus A300s could be at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers working on the problem believe it is probably rare,  
``but what if one, two or five other planes out there have this 
problem?'' asked British Airways technician James O'Sullivan during 
an interview with the Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration minimized the risk to the  
traveling public in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was one event, the only documented event, and it happened  
in uncontrolled airspace,'' FAA spokeswoman Kathryn Creedy said. 
``In the United States, we have air traffic control that is based 
on constant supervision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The incident occurred June 28 as a British Airways Boeing  
747-400 flew east from London to Hong Kong as an older Korean Air 
Boeing 747-200 flew west from Seoul to Tashkent, Uzbekistan. The 
planes converged in cloudy skies over northwest China's 
uncontrolled airspace, but neither flight crew was worried because 
each of their Traffic Alert and Collision Avoidance systems showed 
the other plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Such systems are required on all U.S. airliners, and most  
foreign authorities require them as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Suddenly, the TCAS system in the Korean Air plane called out  
``Climb! Climb!'' As the warning repeated and the pilot pulled his 
aircraft up ever steeper, he brought it up to the altitude of the 
British Air plane. 
</P>
<P>
	The two jets, which should have passed 2,000 feet apart, flashed  
by with just 600 feet between their wing tips. The co-pilot of the 
British Airways plane said the Korean jet seemed to fill his left 
windshield. 
</P>
<P>
	A collision would have been one of the worst on record. The  
Korean plane was a cargo jet with a crew of just three. But the 
British jumbo jet was filled with 419 passengers and crew members. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied Signal said Tuesday that it believes two rare problems  
occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers who analyzed the Korean plane's air data computer, a  
unit built by Bendix, which Allied acquired in 1983, found the 
computer was reading incorrect altitude information. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Allied engineers believe that a pin on a connector that  
allows the air data computer to compare information with a second 
air data computer was bent or pushed back too far, preventing a 
backup check. That problem likely occurred during its installation 
or subsequent maintenance. 
</P>
<P>
	The net result of both malfunctions is that the Korean Air TCAS  
system thought the airplane was at 33,900 feet, when in reality it 
was 2,400 feet below at 31,500 feet. The British Air jet was 
cruising along at 33,500 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Its TCAS system had been getting acceptable readings from the  
Korean Air plane, but as the airplanes converged, the altitude 
information sent out by the Korean Air planed jumped 2,400 feet in 
an instant -- an amount computers aboard the British jet ignored 
initially because such large jumps are unlikely. 
</P>
<P>
	When both systems realized the impending collision, the Korean  
Air plane was told to climb, since its computer thought it was 
already above the British Airways plane. In reality, that nearly 
brought it into the path of the British plane. 
</P>
<P>
	``The facts preliminarily are suggesting this is a particular  
unit failure and in short order we are going to be issuing this 
bulletin to make sure everybody is checked,'' said Allied Signal 
spokesman Dennis Signorovitch. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
