Gold(final) -    $320.30    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.
Silver(final) -   $5.520  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Intel, Microsoft Among Losers  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of Intel, which is often considered a  
bellwether stock for the technology sector, fell 4 9/16 to 72 1/8 
today after its earnings report late yesterday. The world's largest 
manufacturer of semiconductors, said it earned 55 cents a share in 
the third quarter, 2 cents below analysts' expectations. The 
results surprised many investors who have come to expect Intel to 
meet or beat Wall Street forecasts. Several other technology 
leaders also fell, including Microsoft, which was down 1 1/2 at 91 
1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris: Tobacco Isn't Safe  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The world's biggest cigarette company's  
acknowledgment that smoking is dangerous and addictive is spurring 
renewed calls for federal regulation of tobacco and greater efforts 
to keep children from taking their first puff. Philip Morris Cos. 
Inc., which owns the tobacco company that makes best-selling 
Marlboro and other cigarettes, publicly acknowledged with the debut 
of its corporate Internet site that smokers face serious health 
risks. The declarations by Philip Morris follow years in which it 
fiercely argued with government and medical authorities over the 
risks of smoking. President Clinton said Philip Morris' 
acknowledgment that tobacco isn't safe ``comes far too late but 
still we must all welcome it. It can be the beginning of clearing 
the air.'' 

</P>
<P>
	UAW Ratifies GM Pacts  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The United Auto Workers said today that members  
at General Motors Corp. and its former parts plant have ratified a 
four-year contract. Union leaders at Ford Motor Co. approved a new 
contract that guarantees jobs for about 23,500 workers at Ford 
parts plants even if Ford turns its parts division into a separate 
company. The UAW's Ford executive council unanimously recommended 
the four-year deal. Voting by about 100,000 workers is scheduled to 
end Oct. 24. Most of the terms mirror those agreed to by GM and 
DaimlerChrysler AG -- 3 percent raises each year, a $1,350 signing 
bonus and improvements in pensions. 

</P>
<P>
	Auto Sales Up, Except for Ford  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Consumers snapped up cars, trucks, minivans and  
sport utility vehicles at a blistering pace last month, pushing the 
auto industry one step closer to a record year for sales. 
Automakers sold about 1.4 million cars and light trucks in the 
United States last month, an increase of about 9.5 percent over 
last year. Ford Motor Co. was the exception to the sales advance. 
Its sales were off 2 percent last month. The No. 2 automaker said 
sales of its Ford, Lincoln and Mercury cars were down 5 percent, 
mostly because of fewer sales to rental and business fleets. 

</P>
<P>
	Delphi Automotive Earnings Rise  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Delphi Automotive Systems said today its earnings  
improved in the third quarter, partly because of increased sales to 
customers besides its former parent, General Motors Corp. The 
world's largest auto parts maker said it earned $136 million, or 24 
cents a share, compared to a loss of $214 million, or 38 cents a 
share, in the same period last year that was due to a strike at GM 
plants in Flint. The results were a penny a share higher than Wall 
Street predictions. 

</P>
<P>
	Hughes Electronics Posts Loss  
</P>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- Hughes Electronics Corp. lost $29.6  
million in the third quarter, mainly because of expenses from its 
acquisition of two satellite-TV rivals and higher satellite costs. 
The loss for the quarter that ended Sept. 30 amounted to 13 cents a 
share, and compared with a $42.9 million profit, or 11 cents a 
share, in the same period a year ago, Hughes reported today. The 
General Motors subsidiary, whose operations include the nation's 
biggest satellite-television service, had revenues of $1.99 
billion, up from $1.51 billion in the same quarter of 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Cable Gains Boost Time Warner  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner Inc. reported third-quarter net  
income of $360 million, bouncing back from a loss a year ago as big 
gains from cable TV offset weaker results in its music and 
television studios. The world's largest media and entertainment 
company reported its earnings were equivalent to 27 cents per share 
and compared to a loss of $37 million, or 3 cents a share, in the 
same period a year ago. Revenues rose 2 percent to $6.72 billion 
from $6.59 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Y2K Repercussions Could Linger  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Repercussions from Y2K-related computer  
problems could extend well beyond Jan. 1 in many countries and 
involve the United States in humanitarian and environmental crisis 
relief, a CIA official said today. Lawrence Gershwin, the CIA's 
national intelligence officer for science and technology, listed 
Russia, Ukraine, China and Indonesia as among the countries most 
vulnerable to serious millennium bug disruptions. He told the 
Senate's special Y2K panel, that the risks vary from country to 
country: Russia and Ukraine face dangers in their nuclear power, 
gas and electric power industries. Latin America is likely to see 
some disruptions in telecommunications, public health and social 
welfare. Some Asian countries could see problems in railroads, 
ports and medical services. 

</P>
<P>
	Con Ed To Buy Northeast Utilities  
</P>
<P>
	NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Consolidated Edison Inc. today announced  
it was buying Northeast Utilities for about $3.5 billion in cash 
and stock. The merger will create one of the largest electric 
companies in the United States. The deal -- which was preceded by 
several days of Wall Street speculation and a flurry of trading in 
both companies' stocks -- creates a company with more than 6.4 
million electric and gas customers from New York City through New 
England. Company officials said today that merging the two 
utilities could save $1.5 billion in operating expenses over 10 
years. 

</P>
<P>
	SEC Proposes New Mutual Fund Rules  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal securities regulators, seeking to  
better protect the millions of Americans who invest in mutual 
funds, are proposing new rules that would expand the power of 
independent directors of mutual fund companies. The purpose would 
be to better protect the millions of Americans who invest in them. 
The Securities and Exchange Commission voted today 4-0, to seek 
public comment on the proposed rules, which include a requirement 
that the boards of most mutual fund companies have a majority of 
independent directors. Under current rules, 40 percent of fund 
companies' directors must be independent of the company, though 
most large fund companies voluntarily have a majority of 
independent directors. 

</P>
<P>
	ETrade Loss Is Less Than Expected  
</P>
<P>
	MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) -- ETrade Group Inc. reported a  
smaller-than-expected fourth-quarter loss today as it added 310,000 
customers in three months. For the period ending Sept. 30, the 
nation's second-largest Internet brokerage behind Charles Schwab 
reported a loss of $26.7 million, or 11 cents a share, compared to 
a loss of $15.2 million, or 8 cents a share for the same period a 
year ago. Analyses had expected ETrade to lose 13 cents a share, 
according to a survey of analysts by First Call/Thompson Financial. 

</P>
