<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins' Centers To Face Old Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- To say Larry Centers is fired up about his  
first game against Arizona since he left the Cardinals is a massive 
understatement. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31-year-old fullback, the heart and soul of the Cardinals  
for nearly a decade, remains bitter that the team released him in a 
salary-cutting move in the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	He will make his first appearance against his former team Sunday  
night when the Washington Redskins come to Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	``No doubt about it,'' Centers said when asked if he had  
something to prove to the Cardinals' front office. ``The way I 
figure it, I need to do about $1 million worth of damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's roughly the amount of salary cap room the Cardinals saved  
by cutting him. 
</P>
<P>
	Centers said part of the reason he signed with the Redskins was  
that he knew he'd be playing the Cardinals twice each season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm kind of trying to visualize and play it through my mind  
what's going to happen,'' he said Wednesday in a telephone 
conference call. ``And I'm visualizing a lot of good things 
happening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Centers still finds it hard to believe that, after all his years  
of work for Arizona when the franchise was losing, he'd be cut 
loose after the Cardinals finally made the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never visualized myself leaving the organization with a  
bitter taste in my mouth,'' he said. ``Having put so much into it, 
I always envisioned myself going out gracefully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he still talks regularly with Cardinals players. He said  
they've told him many things about this year's Arizona team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to say too much,'' he said, ``but just that it's  
different around there now than it was last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Centers said the Cardinals ruined a good thing with their  
offseason moves. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think their reaction to a little bit of success was not the  
right reaction, but they've proven that in the first five weeks of 
the season,'' Centers said, referring to Arizona's staggering 2-3 
start. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornerback Aeneas Williams, a teammate of Centers for all but  
the first of his years in Arizona, said the Cardinals should be 
forever indebted to Centers. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he did was contagious,'' Williams said. ``The hustle that  
the fans saw on Sunday, we saw every day in practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cornerback J.J. McClesky knows Centers is looking forward to  
this game. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know he's going to be lights out,'' McClesky said, ``but  
the thing about LC is he can't turn it up a notch. There's no way 
he can play harder than he always does anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Centers expects a warm welcome back from the crowd at Sun Devil  
Stadium, maybe even the old ``Lar-ry! Lar-ry!'' chant. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll welcome me back. But I don't think they'll do it at a  
time where it will hurt their team,'' he said. ``I don't think 
they'll do it at a time that will take momentum away from the 
Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Take away the organization and all that stuff, the people  
there have been real nice to me and real cool with me,'' he said. 
``I came there a few weeks ago and I was at the grocery store and a 
lady approached me and said, `I'm really going to miss seeing you 
play.' 
</P>
<P>
	``That kind of stuff is special to me and always will be. What  
really gives me the best feeling is to know that somebody out there 
appreciates the suffering and the dedication and the commitment on 
my part to try to make us a good team, and try to give them their 
money's worth and not short them in any way.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
