<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprise Rent-A-Car Expanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Enterprise Rent-A-Car quietly rose to No. 1 in  
the industry by catering to people with cars in the shop. Now, just 
as quietly, Enterprise is going after the airport rental car 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Without fanfare, the privately-held St. Louis company has more  
than doubled its number of airport offices over the past year, and 
officials say more growth is planned. 
</P>
<P>
	With something less than 2 percent of the current airport  
market, Enterprise has a long way to go before seriously competing 
with the likes of Hertz, Avis and National. But company officials 
believe Enterprise can reach an untapped customer -- the leisure 
traveler, what they call the infrequent flyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a segment of the traveling public which isn't being  
properly served by our competitors,'' said Rob Hibbard, vice 
president of rental development for Enterprise. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people we're going after are the infrequent travelers and  
the value-conscious travelers,'' said Pam Nicholson, senior vice 
president of North American operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Enterprise was founded in 1957. The company has grown rapidly  
since the mid-1980s, when insurance companies began providing their 
clients with rental cars while their vehicles were being repaired. 
In the last four years alone, Enterprise's annual revenues have 
grown from $3.1 billion to $4.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Until recently, Enterprise had for the most part stayed away  
from the airport market, which specializes in providing rental cars 
to business travelers. 
</P>
<P>
	``But in recent years, more and more of our local customers have  
continued to ask us to bring our same high level of customer 
service and value pricing to the airport market,'' said Andrew C. 
Taylor, president and chief executive for Enterprise. 
</P>
<P>
	Hertz has 29 percent of the $9 billion airport market. Avis is  
No. 2 with 23 percent, followed by National with 16 percent and 
Budget with 11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Enterprise officials said they've set no specific goals for  
market share. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rate at which we expand will depend on how we do in  
servicing our customers,'' Hibbard said. ``Our goal is to be the 
best and not necessarily the biggest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Right now, Enterprise has offices at just 38 of the nation's top  
100 airports, though Hibbard said they serve 95 of the top 100 
airports, with shuttle buses transporting customers from airports 
to the off-site Enterprise offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Enterprise also claims to have the price advantage. On average,  
Enterprise claims its rates are 20 percent lower than many of the 
other rental car companies. For a weekly rental, the Enterprise 
customer pays about $75 less than the typical airport car rental 
customer, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hibbard said Enterprise can undercut the cost of competitors  
because of its size. ``We have the advantage of having the 
purchasing power of being the largest rental company in the 
nation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, experts said Enterprise's growing presence shouldn't lead  
to a price war. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're talking about a company that won't have the volume to  
drag down the rates,'' said Jon LeSage, vice president of Abrams 
Travel Data Services in Long Beach, Calif. ``They (Enterprise) are 
not going to be able to service that guy that travels 20 times a 
year on business -- these people have corporate accounts with Hertz, 
Avis, Budget.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
