<HEADLINE> Gregg Popovich Is in Midseason Form </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- In only the first practice since arriving  
for the McDonald's Championship, San Antonio Spurs coach Gregg 
Popovich was in midseason form. 
</P>
<P>
	``Come on, come on! Push it, push it! Whoa, stop! Foul! Shoot  
the free throws and make 'em both!,'' he yelled at various 
junctures Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing a microphone for the benefit of the hundreds of  
spectators allowed in for the public session at a small gym in the 
city center, Popovich chided and cajoled the NBA champions, who 
will be expected to extend the league's 16-game undefeated streak 
in this tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never want to be the first NBA team to lose over here,''  
guard Steve Kerr said. ``There's an element of pride involved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio has a bye into Friday's semifinals, as does European  
champion Zalgiris Kaunas of Lithuania. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday night's first-round games at the 10,122-seat FilaForum  
arena pit South American champion Vasco da Gama of Brazil against 
Australian champion Adelaide 36ers, and Italian League champion 
Varese Roosters against Asian champion C.S. Sagesse of Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	The title game is Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're just going to try to play good, solid defense and give  
ourselves a chance to win the games,'' said Spurs center David 
Robinson, among several players willing to autograph everything 
handed them -- from T-shirts to high-school textbooks -- by eager 
fans after practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great to get the attention that we're getting overseas.  
You can just feel the excitement in the whole building,'' said 
guard Avery Johnson, whom the crowd serenaded with chants of ``A-V, 
A-V.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They were cheering for everything,'' Johnson said. ``Passes,  
jump shots, dunks, everything. The excitement is different over 
here. You can feel it on every single play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There isn't likely to be a lot of excitement for those rooting  
against the Spurs at the tournament, even if there is some 
NBA-level talent on Zalgiris Kaunas. 
</P>
<P>
	While the team lost two players with NBA experience, Tyus Edney  
and Anthony Bowie, in the offseason, it still can rely on the 
inside presence provided by 6-foot-11 George Zidek, a member of 
UCLA's 1995 NCAA champions, and 7-1 Eurelijus Zukauskas, whose NBA 
rights are owned by the Milwaukee Bucks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lithuanian club also has Corey Beck, who helped Arkansas win  
the 1994 NCAA title and has seen NBA action with the Charlotte 
Hornets and Detroit Pistons. 
</P>
<P>
	Popovich, treating these games as preseason, is likely to  
shuttle in all 15 players he brought. 
</P>
<P>
	``On any given night, one person could definitely have an  
off-night,'' finals MVP Tim Duncan said, ``but not all of us are 
going to.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
