<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Bear Stearns &AMP; Cos., down 3 1/2 at 36 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	Bear Stearns became the first Wall Street securities firm to  
miss earnings expectations for the recently ended quarter, posting 
profits of $157.9 million, or $1 a share. Analysts had expected 
Bear Stearns to earn $1.15 per share in the quarter, its fiscal 
first. 

</P>
<P>
 *ZDNet Group, up 2 1/2 at 22 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs raised its rating on the stock to ``trading buy''  
from ``outperform,'' citing strong advertising demand. The analyst 
also said ZDNet, a unit of Ziff-Davis Inc., is undervalued relative 
to other online publishers. 

</P>
<P>
 *Chris-Craft Industries Inc., up 7 1/2 at 66    	
</P>
<P>
	Chris-Craft, the owner of 10 television stations, is considering  
a sale of all or part of its business for as much as $3.5 billion, 
The Wall Street Journal reported. Potential suitors include CBS 
Corp., News Corp. and Tribune Co., the newspaper said. 

</P>
<P>
 *Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch Inc., down 6 3/16 at 26 5/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Shares of the casual clothing retailer tumbled as the company  
said it will meet but is unlikely to exceed analysts' forecasts for 
third-quarter earnings of 31 cents per share. Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch 
has beaten estimates in every quarter since it went public. 

</P>
<P>
 *Storage Technology Corp., down 4 11/16 at 14 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	The company, a maker of data storage and retrieval products,  
said third-quarter earnings and revenue will fall well below 
analysts' estimates. Storage Technology cited delayed orders as 
customers anticipate Year 2000 computer problems. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Intel Corp., down 4 9/16 at 72 1/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Intel's third-quarter earnings missed analysts' forecasts of 57  
cents per share. Intel, the world's largest manufacturer of 
semiconductors, earned $1.9 billion, or 55 cents a share, in the 
quarter. 

</P>
<P>
 *Intergraph Corp., down 1 15/32 at 4 1/32    	
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge ruled Tuesday that Intel owned the right to key  
patent licenses that Intergraph claimed were its own. The ruling 
reversed an earlier decision in favor of Intergraph. 

</P>
<P>
 *Nextel Communications Inc., down 6 at 71    	
</P>
<P>
	Shares fell for a second straight day after Nextwave Telecom  
Inc. said it won't sell wireless communications licenses to Nextel. 
Analysts said Nextel, a wireless phone company, might not have a 
big enough piece of the airwaves to meet future needs for advanced 
wireless Internet and data services. 


  	   	
</P>
