<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flood of Stamps Planned for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- From Navy submarines to deep-sea creatures,  
from the Stars and Stripes to stars in the sky, from the Year of 
the Dragon to Wile E. Coyote, next year's postage stamps explore a 
wide range of people and issues. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be stamps for author Thomas Wolfe, war heroes Audie  
Murphy, and Alvin York, and political leaders Claude Pepper and 
Patricia Roberts Harris, the Postal Service announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Postmaster General William Henderson said the new stamps ``will  
help bring pride and a little passion to that unique moment in 
everyone's day when we go through our mail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opening the year will be the Year of the Dragon, celebrating the  
lunar new year, continuing the annual series of animals featured in 
the Chinese calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	But the second holiday stamp won't arrive until fall, when  
Thanksgiving will be marked with a cornucopia stamp. The stamp also 
will commemorate the United Nations' designation of 2000 as an 
International Year of Thanksgiving. 
</P>
<P>
	The traditional Christmas stamp will be a Madonna by artist Jan  
Gossaert, now hanging in the Art Institute of Chicago. Santa will 
appear on the contemporary stamp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars and Stripes will get plenty of attention in 2000, with  
a panel of 20 different flags charting the evolution of the U.S. 
flag from colonial times. The 200th anniversary of the executive 
mansion will be marked with a White House stamp. 
</P>
<P>
	An adoption stamp will continue the tradition of using stamps to  
raise awareness of social issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Patricia Roberts Harris, the first black woman to serve in the  
Cabinet and the first black woman to be a U.S. ambassador, will 
appear on the Black Heritage stamp in 2000. Harris was ambassador 
to Luxembourg under President Johnson and held two Cabinet posts 
under President Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	Other individuals honored on stamps will include sculptor Louise  
Nevelson, author Thomas Wolfe and Claude Pepper, a congressman 
known for his advocacy on behalf of the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	The military will be honored with a five-stamp series depicting  
Navy submarines and four stamps honoring distinguished soldiers 
Alvin C. York, John L. Hines, Audie L. Murphy and Omar N. Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronomer Edwin Powell Hubble and the Hubble Space Telescope --  
named for him -- will be honored in a series of five stamps 
featuring images of stars, galaxies and nebulas. A separate 
four-stamp set will look at the achievements of the U.S. space 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	One stamp set will feature the Pacific Coast rain forest, and  
five other stamps will look at deep-sea creatures. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports fans will find track featured on a summer sports stamp  
and a set of stamps will feature youth sports programs, including 
basketball, football, soccer and baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	For folks with a sense of humor, the cartoon characters series  
continues, this year honoring the ever-frustrated Wile E. Coyote 
and his nemesis, the Road Runner. 
</P>
<P>
	The centennial of U.S. sovereignty over American Samoa will be  
recalled in a stamp, as will the 150th anniversary of California 
statehood. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
