<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Committee Polling Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- The Republican National Committee is  
polling members on whether New Hampshire and Iowa should keep their 
first-in-the-nation ritual when it comes to picking presidential 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson mailed the survey to the RNC's  
165 members on Oct. 5. The results are nonbinding, but could be 
used to propose a new nominating process at an RNC meeting in San 
Jose, Calif., in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey asks whether members believe there are problems with  
the Republican nominating system, and if so, what. It also asks, 
``If the process is reformed, should Iowa and New Hampshire retain 
their first-in-the-nation status?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa and New Hampshire currently are haggling over dates for  
their contests, traditionally held eight days apart. Iowa has 
scheduled its caucuses for Jan. 31, and New Hampshire delivered a 
shocker by scheduling its primary for Feb. 1 -- a day later. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a perfect world, I think Iowa and New Hampshire would both  
tell you we would prefer not to have that question in there,'' 
Steve Duprey, chairman of the New Hampshire Republican party, said 
Tuesday. ``We've gotten used to this primary and think of it as our 
right. That view is not shared around the country. ... I think 
frankly we are an underdog in this effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The survey is part of an attempt to stop states from holding  
increasingly earlier presidential primaries. About 25 states will 
hold primaries and caucuses between the end of January and March 14 
-- turning the nominating season from a marathon into a dash before 
many voters typically start paying attention to the election. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey requests comments on four alternatives, including  
establishment of rotating, regional primaries -- a proposal already 
embraced by the National Association of Secretaries of State. 
</P>
<P>
	The surveys are due Oct. 25; the results will be reviewed Oct.  
27, Duprey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duprey and the national committee members from New Hampshire,  
Ruth Griffin and Tom Rath, have mailed letters to other RNC members 
to try to convince them of the importance of New Hampshire's 
primary. 
</P>
<P>
	``We understand that the first primary is an enormous political  
privilege, but we believe we have earned it over the last 50 years 
with voter turnouts in excess of 75 percent, with a large and 
involved core of activists, and with a statewide attention and 
focus on the event that is total,'' the letter reads. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, several states, including Washington, Michigan and  
Louisiana, unsuccessfully have challenged Iowa's leadoff caucuses 
and New Hampshire's leadoff primary. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
