<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Delays Newspaper Shutdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- A federal judge has blocked the scheduled  
shutdown of the Honolulu Star-Bulletin until the state's antitrust 
lawsuit against the newspaper's owner and its only competitor is 
decided. 
</P>
<P>
	The state argued that newspaper giant Gannett Co. Inc. -- which  
owns the morning Honolulu Advertiser -- in effect paid off the owner 
of the afternoon Star-Bulletin to create its own monopoly. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for both Gannett and the Star-Bulletin's owner said  
the agreement was a business decision beneficial to both and 
violates no federal laws. 
</P>
<P>
	In issuing the temporary injunction Wednesday, U.S. District  
Judge Alan Kay said the public interest to preserve separate 
editorial voices in the community is great enough to keep the 
Star-Bulletin running until the lawsuit is settled. 
</P>
<P>
	He ordered that no further actions be taken to impede the  
continued operation of the 117-year-old Star-Bulletin -- including 
ending its joint operating agreement with the Advertiser. 
</P>
<P>
	The Advertiser said Gannett would appeal the injunction.  
</P>
<P>
	Some Star-Bulletin newspaper boxes had already been removed and  
Star-Bulletin subscribers had been notified that their 
subscriptions would be converted to Advertiser subscriptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the joint operating agreement, the two share advertising,  
circulation and business operations, but maintain separate 
newsrooms and editorial staffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Star-Bulletin general partner Rupert Phillips and Gannett  
announced last month that the joint operating agreement would be 
terminated Oct. 30 and the Star-Bulletin would close. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange, Phillips' Liberty Newspapers Limited Partnership  
would receive a payment -- $26.5 million, according to court records 
-- based on the savings Gannett could expect from ending the joint 
operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Attorney General Rodney Kimura said that $26.5 million  
was Gannett's assurance that Liberty Newspapers does not put the 
Star-Bulletin up for sale, and he equated it to a payoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Entering an agreement that eliminates the Star-Bulletin as a  
competitor to the Advertiser is a violation of federal antitrust 
law, Kimura said. He urged Liberty Newspapers to sell the 
Star-Bulletin rather than closing it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're back in business, but we're not out of the woods yet,''  
Star-Bulletin Publisher John Flanagan said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Marx, representing Liberty Newspapers, said the agreement  
with Gannett was based on profitability. Phillips has said the 
paper earns a 12 percent return while mainland papers are earning 
double that, so his investors want to look elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``The laws of economics can't be repealed by the Newspaper  
Preservation Act,'' Marx said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
