<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cone vs. Ramon Martinez in Game 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The opposing starters for Game 2 of the American  
League playoffs share a common background -- that terrible moment 
when a pitcher's arm no longer responds. 
</P>
<P>
	David Cone of the New York Yankees, who went through it a couple  
of years ago, knows just what's going through the mind of Boston's 
Ramon Martinez, who experienced it more recently. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing like it,'' Cone said. ``The expectation levels  
you have for yourself are confusing. You don't know what to 
expect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cone has seen his share of surgeons. He had an aneurism in his  
right arm during the 1996 season, when he was limited to 11 starts. 
Then there was surgery on his right shoulder following the 1997 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez had rotator cuff surgery on his right shoulder last  
year and was released by the Los Angeles Dodgers. He signed on with 
Boston, where his brother, Pedro, was already the mainstay of the 
staff. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, Martinez rebuilt his career with 10 rehabilitation  
starts in the minors and a 3-1 record in four starts with the Red 
Sox. Meanwhile, Cone punctuated his career with the 14th perfect 
game in modern major league history in a 12-9 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Cone admired the Red Sox pitcher's progress.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a remarkable comeback,'' he said. ``It's very emotional,  
sort of a tough thing to deal with to contain the emotion that your 
arm is back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez's rehab itinerary was right out of a travel agent's  
dream -- Fort Meyers, Fla., Sarasota, Fla., Lowell, Mass., 
Pawtucket, R.I. and finally Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``He put a lot of air miles on this year, maybe bus miles,  
too,'' manager Jimy Williams said. ``The kid kept working and he 
never stopped one day from doing whatever he felt was helping him 
come back and helping our team win. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a game in Oakland, an afternoon game. It was the eighth  
inning and I see this kid go down to the bullpen and throwing. I am 
saying why is he going down there and throwing. He still felt in 
his mind he could pitch and help us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez is matter of fact about his comeback.  
</P>
<P>
	``They give me the chance, and here I am,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
