<HEADLINE> AL Playoffs Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Scott Brosius was the World Series MVP last  
year, so postseason heroics are nothing new to him. 
</P>
<P>
	But he came within a double of doing something he's never done --  
and nobody else has, either. 
</P>
<P>
	With a home run, a triple and a single, Brosius had a chance to  
be the first person ever to hit for the cycle. He came up in the 
ninth inning needing a double, but struck out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got the triple out of the way and I just don't get too many  
of those,'' he said. ``I was just trying to get on base and if it 
happened with a double, it would have just been that much more 
fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brosius batted .471 with two homers and six RBIs in New York's  
four-game sweep of the San Diego Padres in last year's series. 
Against Texas in the first round this year, he was 1-for-10 with 
one RBI. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the postseason,'' he said. ``It's something as a player  
that you hope you have the opportunity to do. ... I just treat 
every game as a must-win game and just feel like I have a lot of 
intensity in every game.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``LONG LIVE THE KING?:@ Jim Leyritz is called ``The King'' --  
mostly by himself -- but the king won't rule in the AL championship 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees utilityman was dropped from the playoff  
roster on Wednesday so the team could add Shane Spencer as 
insurance for Paul O'Neill's broken rib. Both O'Neill and Spencer 
were in the starting lineup for Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very difficult, no question,'' Yankees manager Joe  
Torre said. ``Jimmy struggled near the end of the season. It didn't 
keep me from going to him in Games 1 and 2.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer starred in the 1998 playoff series against Texas, going  
3-for-6 with two homers and six RBIs. But he was 1-for-10 against 
Cleveland in the next round and got just three at-bats in the World 
Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer hit .234 with eight homers and 20 RBIs during the 1999  
season but was cut for the roster for the first round of the 
playoffs against the Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz was acquired from San Diego on July 31 and hit .227 with  
five RBIs in 66 at-bats for the Yankees during the regular season. 
He was 0-for-2 in the first round against the Texas Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of Leyritz's 12 postseason hits have been home runs,  
including a three-run shot for the Yankees in Game 4 of the 1996 
World Series against Atlanta to tie the it 6-6. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, we'll get through this round and see what happens  
next round,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill hurt himself Oct. 2 running into a fence trying to catch  
a foul ball at Tampa Bay. Torre wasn't sure O'Neill could play 
until talking with the right fielder on Wednesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't put up a lineup until after he got here today,''  
Torre said. ``We talked about it. I saw how anxious he was to 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another alternative would have been to cut rookie Clay  
Bellinger, one of the few Yankees with speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel a little more secure having a pinch runner, especially  
Clay, who can play all around, too,'' Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PERFECT ROTATION:* The first three pitchers in the Boston Red  
Sox rotation have pitched no-hitters, sort of. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's Game 1 starter, Kent Mercker, threw a no-hitter in  
1994 when he was with the Atlanta Braves, striking out 10 to beat 
the Los Angeles Dodgers 6-0. He also pitched an unofficial 
no-hitter, combining with Mark Wohlers and Alejandro Pena to beat 
San Diego 1-0 in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramon Martinez, who starts Game 2, pitched his no-hitter against  
the Florida Marlins in 1995, striking out eight in a 7-0 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedro Martinez was with Montreal when he was perfect through  
nine innings against San Diego. But Bip Roberts led off the 10th 
inning with a double to cost Martinez his gem, and Mel Rojas 
finished the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't expect the Yankees to be intimidated, though: Game 2  
starter David Cone pitched a perfect game against Montreal on July 
18 this year. And Game 3 starter Roger Clemens has a nice little 
record of his own, twice striking out a major-league record 20 
batters while he was with Boston. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *REVENGE:* Add Red Sox infielder Lou Merloni to the list of New  
Englanders scarred by Bucky Dent's home run in the 1978 playoff 
game to decide the AL East champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was at home crying. There's a lot of moments, like Righetti  
throwing a no-hitter'' against Boston in 1983, Merloni said. 
``Hopefully there'll be some kind of memory etched into some kid's 
stone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox and Yankees finished tied at the end of the '78  
season, then played one game at Fenway Park on Oct. 2 to decide who 
would play Kansas City for the AL pennant. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston led 2-0 after six innings before the light-hitting Dent  
hit a three-run homer in the top of the seventh to give New York 
the lead for good. 
</P>
<P>
	That's considered a regular-season game. The Yankees and Red Sox  
have never met in the playoffs; until the advent of the wild card, 
it was impossible because they have always been in the same league 
and division. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *EXTRA BASES:* Rivera only threw two innings once in the regular  
season. ... The Red Sox have dropped nine consecutive AL 
championship series games -- the longest in either league. ... The 
Yankees' 11 consecutive postseason wins is the second-longest in 
baseball history. The longest was 12 when they swept the 1927, '28 
and '32 World Series. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
