<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Markets Fall With Wall St. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices retreated around the world today  
following a selloff Tuesday on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average was off about 87  
points at the 10,329 level in midday trading, adding to its 231.12 
point, or 2.2. percent, decline of Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader U.S. market indicators also fell today as investors,  
already worried about higher interest rates, were rattled by a 
disappointing earnings report from chip maker Intel. The market had 
looked forward to strong third-quarter earnings; the unpleasant 
surprise from Intel and an earnings warning from defense contractor 
Raytheon punctured that optimism. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, the benchmark FTSE 100 index dropped 0.99 percent  
today, on top of Tuesday's 60-point loss. Frankfurt, Germany's 
Xetra Dax was down 1.18 percent and the CAC-40 index in Paris was 
off 1.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average  
fell 1.9 percent, and Hong Kong's blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 
2.2 percent. The Straits Times Index in Singapore slipped 1.1 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Jitters about a possible rise in interest rates added to  
wariness in Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	A 4.9 percent increase in average earnings in Britain, along  
with a continued rise in house prices, stoked fears that the Bank 
of England would raise interest rates next month to keep the 
economy from overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese traders were cautious in advance of a Bank of Japan  
meeting and expectations that the central bank would probably not 
act decisively to blunt the advance of the yen against the U.S. 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Many in Japan are worried that the strengthening yen could choke  
off a delicate economic recovery by making Japanese exports too 
expensive abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan later decided to leave its easy-money policy  
unchanged, and to start outright purchases of short-term government 
bonds, putting more yen in circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar got a lift from the decision. In New York trading  
this morning, the dollar had climbed to 107.78 yen from 106.31 yen 
late Tuesday. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
