<DOCNO> APW19991013.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 01:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wilt Transformed Game of Basketball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Wilt Chamberlain's transformation from Big Dipper to defensive  
demon might have been his most amazing achievement in a career 
filled with gargantuan records. 
</P>
<P>
	During the time he stalked NBA courts, ladling in baskets as if  
he were pouring cream into a cup, he made opposing centers fear his 
shadow. Chamberlain himself lived in the shadow of another, smaller 
center -- Bill Russell. 
</P>
<P>
	The Big Dipper scored 100 points in a single game, scored 50 or  
more a record 118 times. He caused rules to be changed, defenses to 
be modified and coaches to be fired. He had a fadeaway bank shot, a 
turnaround stuff shot, a finger-rolling flip shot, and a most 
dreadful two-handed underhand foul shot. He used them all to become 
the most prolific scorer in NBA history with 31,419 points until 
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar surpassed him more than a decade after he 
retired. 
</P>
<P>
	But throughout most of his incredible career, the 7-foot-1,  
280-pound Chamberlain was pegged a loser. A great scorer, 
certainly, but no team man, critics said. Russell, at 6-foot-9, was 
the center everyone talked about when they talked about the best 
because the Celtics almost always won the title. Four times, 
Chamberlain won the Most Valuable Player award, but Russell won it 
five times. 
</P>
<P>
	Chamberlain's 76ers broke through the infallibility of Russell's  
Celtics only once -- during the 1966-67 season when they ran off 68 
victories in 82 games and walked away with the NBA title. 
Chamberlain averaged 24.3 points that year, only the second time in 
his career at that stage that he averaged less than 33.5. He didn't 
lead the league in scoring, but he led it in rebounding and was 
third in assists. Chamberlain always could do pretty much anything 
he wanted on the court, and that season he made up his mind to 
outrebound, outpass and out-Russell Russell. 
</P>
<P>
	The Big Dipper faded away and Wilt the winner appeared.  
</P>
<P>
	Chamberlain never again averaged more than 27.3 points. After  
his 1968 trade to Los Angeles, he scored a career low 20.5 points, 
but led the Lakers into the finals, where they lost -- to Boston 
again -- in seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1969-70 season was a washout for Chamberlain, who injured  
his knee early and appeared in only 12 regular-season games. Still, 
the Lakers pulled themselves into the finals, where they were 
defeated by New York -- once more in seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	Chamberlain's transformation became complete in the 1971-72  
season as his third Lakers coach, Bill Sharman, entered the scene. 
Sharman came from the school of Boston's Red Auerbach, which, of 
course, was the same school Russell came from. Sharman hired 
another former Celtic, guard K.C. Jones, as an assistant. Together, 
Sharman and Jones molded the potential of the Lakers' superstars 
into a unit that won 33 games in a row, 69 out of 82 during the 
regular season, beat the tough Chicago Bulls four straight in the 
first playoff series, whipped the 1970-71 champion Milwaukee Bucks 
in six games for the Western Conference title, and beat the Knicks 
for the NBA championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Sharman's tutelage, Chamberlain developed the art of  
setting up the fast break in much the same way Russell did it under 
Auerbach. Instead of handing the ball off to a guard after a 
rebound as he had been doing, Chamberlain began flinging passes 
half the length of the court to breaking guards and forwards. 
</P>
<P>
	The result was that the Lakers now scored before opponents could  
get back on defense. Rather than working the ball around for shots, 
they raced in for uncontested layups. Sharman taught the Lakers to 
begin their offense on defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Chamberlain dominated games with his shot blocking, rebounding  
and passing, just as Russell always had. West, always a great 
shooter, allowed his style to blend into Sharman's system and also 
found the transition appealing. West began passing more, Gail 
Goodrich began shooting more, and Jim McMillian started running 
more, while Chamberlain and Happy Hairston cleared the boards. 
Chamberlain's towering presence in the pivot on defense forced 
opponents to shoot from the outside and take poor percentage shots. 
</P>
<P>
	At 35, Chamberlain finally gained the recognition he always  
craved as the complete ballplayer when his need to score no longer 
exceeded his desire to win. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
