<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harvard To Pay Millions in Back Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Harvard University will pay millions of  
dollars in back pay and benefits to 300 to 500 misclassified 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The university announced it had reached an agreement with the  
Harvard Union of Clerical &AMP; Technical Workers on Tuesday, two 
months after the university acknowledged misclassifying the 
employees as casual workers, not full-time employees. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the union contract, anyone working at the  
university for three months must be classified as a full-time 
employee. The contract defines a casual employee as someone who 
works less than 17 1/2 hours per week. 
</P>
<P>
	Compensation will be based on a formula assessing the number of  
hours a casual employee worked, along with length of service. 
</P>
<P>
	The violations began four years ago, said union director Bill  
Jaeger, who helped draft the agreement. The individual amounts 
range from $250 to $12,000, to be paid out over three years, Jaeger 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvard also will offer a large number of workers from the group  
both full-time employment and monetary compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	The exact amount of the payout is not known, but it will be ``in  
the millions,'' said Ann Taylor, Harvard's general counsel and vice 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Union president Adrienne Landeau said it was encouraging that  
Harvard was willing to fix the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were able to be our usual tenacious, but highly civil,  
selves because the university recognized that this was an important 
issue,'' Landeau told The Boston Globe. ``And it knew this 
agreement was the right thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With 3,600 members, HUCTW is the university's largest union.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
