<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Attack N. Korea Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is engaged in ``a  
one-sided love affair'' with North Korea, helping it build reactors 
that would produce enough plutonium for 100 nuclear bombs a year, a 
Republican lawmaker contended Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But former Defense Secretary William Perry, special presidential  
adviser on North Korea, said a 1994 multinational pact will prevent 
North Korea from building the massive processor needed to make that 
fuel weapons-grade. 
</P>
<P>
	Several GOP House members grilled Perry and other Clinton  
administration officials on allegations that the North Koreans have 
misused heavy oil shipments and food aid from the United States and 
that North Korean diplomats have engaged in drug-running, among 
other things. 
</P>
<P>
	The rekindled Republican criticism of President Clinton's  
handling of North Korea was prompted by a report by Perry in which 
he largely endorsed the present approach. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, released Tuesday, credited the 1994 agreement among  
North Korea, the United States, South Korea and Japan with 
preventing Pyongyang from producing nuclear bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	Perry recommended sticking to the pact, a $5 billion deal in  
which North Korea agreed to freeze production of weapons-grade 
plutonium in exchange for fuel oil and construction of two 
light-water nuclear reactors for energy that would not produce 
weapons-grade nuclear materials. It has resulted in U.S. shipment 
of $200 million worth of fuel oil to North Korea. The United States 
separately has given food aid worth more than $460 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., part of a House GOP task force  
developing its own North Korea policy, said, ``U.S. policy is 
conducting a one-sided love affair with the regime in North 
Korea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox contended the light-water reactors could produce enough  
plutonium to make 100 nuclear bombs a year. But Perry said the 
agreement would prohibit that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody in this Congress or administration is in love with the  
administration of North Korea,'' said Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y. 
``They're condemnable.'' But he applauded steps taken to decrease 
dangers on the Korean peninsula. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a recent easing of some sanctions, the government in  
Pyongyang remains under other sanctions as a sponsor of terrorism, 
said Perry. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Joe Knollenberg, R-Mich., citing a report by the General  
Accounting Office -- Congress' investigative branch -- said a system 
to monitor the use of U.S. heavy oil sent to North Korea to meet 
its power needs until the reactors are built failed several times. 
The GAO also found that more oil appeared to be used when the 
system was down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before we spend any additional taxpayer dollars on aid to  
North Korea, Congress and the American people deserve to know 
whether North Korea is living up to its end of the bargain,'' 
Knollenberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department has acknowledged that about 5 percent of  
the heavy fuel oil may have been used for unauthorized purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate GAO report released Tuesday, investigators found  
problems with the tracking of food aid because of reporting 
failures and access restrictions by the Pyongyang government. 
</P>
<P>
	Wendy Sherman, State Department counselor, said U.S. officials  
believe the bulk of food aid is getting to the children for whom it 
is intended, citing the marked improvement in children's health 
reported by relief groups working in North Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Sherman also said the State Department was investigating reports  
that North Korean embassies around the world are financing 
themselves by selling illegal drugs. Rep. John Cooksey, R-La., 
provided a list of 34 North Koreans arrested on drug charges in 
various countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a serious issue about which we're trying to develop  
information,'' Sherman said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said U.S. officials also are closely watching activity by  
several hundred North Koreans in Congo, where uranium is mined. But 
she said there is ``no reason to believe North Korea is mining 
uranium in the Congo.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
