<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Historic Launch Pad To Be Blown Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Like gleeful little boys, rocket  
scientists and launch pad workers could hardly wait for today's 
demolition of historic Launch Complex 41. 
</P>
<P>
	Just the thought of blowing up a launch pad -- on purpose -- was  
irresistible for a crowd accustomed to preventing explosions at all 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to kid you. This is a fun event for us,'' said  
Adrian Laffitte, a launch manager for rocket maker Lockheed Martin 
Corp., which wanted the pad flattened to make way for more modern 
launch facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan was for 180 pounds of explosives to bring down the two  
steel launch towers at Complex 41. That's 7 million pounds of steel 
in all. 
</P>
<P>
	Built in 1965, Launch Complex 41 was the starting point for  
NASA's Viking missions to Mars and Voyager missions to the outer 
planets, and innumerable spy satellites. In all, 27 Titan rockets 
blasted off from the pad. 
</P>
<P>
	To rid the pad of its two launch towers, unnecessary for the  
company's new line of Atlas V rockets, Lockheed Martin opted for 
the quickest, cheapest method: explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also decided to throw a party.  
</P>
<P>
	After all, the last time a Cape Canaveral launch pad was  
deliberately blown up was back in 1976, when John Glenn's 
deteriorating pad was brought down by the Army -- hardly a festive 
affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of workers at Cape Canaveral Air Station planned to  
gather a safe 2,500 feet away to watch the explosion. Hundreds if 
not thousands of others at the Air Force station and NASA's 
adjoining Kennedy Space Center were expected to view the show from 
afar. 
</P>
<P>
	To raise money for needy families at Christmas, Lockheed Martin  
sold more than 300 raffle tickets, at $5 each, for the chance to 
push a make-believe detonation plunger. (The real button will be 
pushed by the pros.) An Air Force engineer won the honor. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also sold 270 T-shirts emblazoned with ``Blasting  
out of the Past'' for $10 each. More are on order. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many others, Air Force Lt. Col. Anthony Goins, a launch  
squadron commander, had mixed feelings about watching Launch 
Complex 41 come down. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been getting a lot of phone calls, especially from a lot  
of our retired workforce that have a lot of sentimental value with 
the pad. I mean, it's been in existence for 34 years,'' Goins said. 
On the other hand, ``We're excited that this is what is going to 
lead us into the future.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991013.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 17:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
