<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Perez Has Them Saying: `Javy Who?' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Javy who?  
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta Braves fans probably won't forget two-time All-Star  
catcher Javy Lopez, but for the time being Eddie Perez will do just 
fine. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Turner Field crowd of 44,624 chanting, ``Eddie!  
Eddie!'' Perez hit the first pitch from Kenny Rogers for a two-run 
home run to cap a four-run, sixth-inning rally Wednesday in a 4-3 
Braves victory over the New York Mets and a 2-0 lead in the 
best-of-7 National League Championship Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the easiest name for them to say,'' Perez said of the  
crowd's chant. ``I'm not really thinking about that. I just try to 
do a good job so they keep cheering for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He wasn't sure what he hit for the homer.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was a changeup,'' he said, ``but to tell you the  
truth, I was looking for a curveball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The homer into the left field seats was his second of the series  
-- he also hit one in Game 1 in Atlanta's 4-2 victory Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eddie may not hit 35-40 home runs like Javy, but him hitting  
home runs is not unusual. He's hit some big ones before,'' Braves 
manager Bobby Cox said. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, who was 2-for-4 in the game and went 2-for-3 Tuesday  
night, is a career 7-for-11 in NLCS play. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, known primarily as the guy who catches Greg Maddux every  
fifth day during his first three years with the Braves, became 
Atlanta's starter when Lopez was lost for the season on July 25 
with a right knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, a .259 career hitter with 24 home runs and 101 RBIs,  
batted .249 with seven homers and 30 RBIs this season in 104 games, 
starting a career-high 89 games. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't think the fans will forget Lopez.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think so. I think next year they'll forget about me  
when Javy is back playing every day,'' Perez said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OLD HAT:* Tom Glavine will be making his 25th postseason start  
and 13th NLCS appearance when he pitches Friday in New York in Game 
3. 
</P>
<P>
	``No. It never gets old. That's what we play for every year, for  
us to be here and have a chance to go for the championship. So it's 
still a lot of fun,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine is 9-11 in the postseason, only 3-8 in the NLCS, but  
owns a 13-5 career mark against the Mets and was 3-0 against them 
this season. Overall, the left-hander was 14-11 during the regular 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	In the ALCS, Glavine, a native of Massachusetts, is rooting for  
the Red Sox in the series with the New York Yankees. Boston beat 
Cleveland 12-8 Monday night to win the best-of-5 series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the kid in me is happy for the Red Sox. I'm still a  
Red Sox fan,'' he said. ``Monday night watching that game, my 
sister, who still lives up there, must have called me 15 times 
during the course of the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LOONY LEITER:* Al Leiter, the Mets scheduled Game 3 pitcher, is  
considered weird and doesn't deny it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm left-handed. I guess you can go from there. I like to have  
fun. I joke around a lot,'' said Leiter, who was 13-12 during the 
regular season and has a 1-1 postseason record, including a loss to 
the Braves in the 1997 NLCS when he was with Florida, which beat 
Atlanta and won the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lets face it, we're playing a baseball game. Yes, it's  
serious, yes, I want to win, but I goof around maybe a little bit 
more than most,'' said Leiter, who was 0-2 against the Braves this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *REMLINGER SIGNS: The Braves announced prior to Game 2 of the  
NLCS that left-handed reliever Mike Remlinger had agreed to a 
two-year contract extension worth $3.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Remlinger, 33, was 10-1 with a 2.37 ERA and one save during the  
1999 regular season in which he was paid $1.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike has done a remarkable job for us,'' Atlanta general  
manager John Schuerholz said. ``He has really been sort of a 
linchpin kind of performer for us out the bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel so strongly about that we're very happy to have him  
under contract and he feels very much the same way,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Remlinger will make $1.4 million in 2000, $1.6 million in 2001  
with a club option of $2 million with a $200,000 buyout for 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Remlinger came to the Braves along with second baseman Bret  
Boone in November in a deal with the Cincinnati Reds for pitcher 
Denny Neagle, outfielder Michael Tucker and minor league pitcher 
Rob Bell. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
