<HEADLINE> Actress Dale Evans Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VICTORVILLE, Calif. (AP) -- Dale Evans, the western movie star  
and widow of Roy Rogers, was hospitalized in serious condition with 
heart problems and respiratory difficulties. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans, 86, was listed in serious condition at Loma Linda  
University Medical Center, hospital spokeswoman Jennifer 
Resch-Silvestri said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tests show she may have suffered a mild heart attack, said her  
grandson, Dustin Rogers. He said she is feisty and eager to leave 
the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's doing real well,'' he said. ``Her spirits are really  
high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evans was admitted to Desert Valley Hospital on Monday and was  
transferred Tuesday to be closer to her cardiologist, Rogers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her illness may have been prompted by a diet change and  
exhaustion from a Lone Pine film festival last weekend, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans starred in 35 movies and a 1950s television series with  
her husband and co-wrote his theme song ``Happy Trails to You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She has also written dozens of inspirational books and hosts a  
cable television talk show on the Trinity Broadcast Network. 
</P>
<P>
	She suffered a stroke in 1996 and a heart attack in 1992.  
</P>
<P>
	Her husband died at the couple's Apple Valley home in 1998 from  
congestive heart failure. He was 86. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
