<DOCNO> APW19991013.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 22:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Model May Help Predict Hurricanes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It may be easier to accurately predict the intensity of a  
hurricane than scientists believe, researchers reported today in 
suggesting meteorologists have not been considering the most 
relevant forces behind a storm's power. 
</P>
<P>
	In today's issue of the journal Nature, researchers unveiled a  
simple simulation that accurately predicted the strengthening and 
weakening of hurricanes by concentrating on the storms' interaction 
with ocean water. 
</P>
<P>
	``The motivation is to try to understand what controls the  
intensity of hurricanes,'' said Kerry Emanuel, an atmospheric 
science professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 
``But I hope to be able to use it for real prediction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters have been reliably determining the path of the  
dangerous storms for about 30 years. But attempts to predict 
changes in intensity beyond 12 hours have not fared so well, 
Emanuel said. 
</P>
<P>
	The uncertainty can be costly in both lives and money: Small,  
non-threatening storms can strengthen without warning. Or large 
storms could lead to massive evacuations before unexpectedly fading 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	Emanuel's system focuses on how the ocean responds to the storm  
and how the storm reacts to the ocean. A hurricane's power 
originates from warm water on the surface of the ocean. At the same 
time, cold water that is churned up by the storm saps its power. 
</P>
<P>
	Using historical data, the simulation accurately predicted the  
strengthening of Hurricanes Hugo, Andrew and Opal. It also 
correctly estimated changes in intensity for several storms this 
year, although the results were not shared with hurricane 
forecasters. 
</P>
<P>
	The system did not work so well on Hurricane Floyd, however,  
perhaps because an earlier storm churned up colder water than 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone buys the model.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's too simplified,'' said William Gray, a Colorado State  
University professor who has been studying and predicting 
hurricanes for 40 years. ``If it was that simple, they would be 
forecasting intensity change much better than they are.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
