<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas Arena Beams Tested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Arena workers stacked thousands  
of water containers in the upper deck of a new arena Wednesday to 
test the strength of its beams after safety concerns forced 
cancellation of an NBA exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-gallon jugs and buckets were intended to simulate the  
weight of a large crowd in 18,000-seat Alltel Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The test was suggested by engineers who on Tuesday told arena  
officials that they wanted to monitor the arena's 22 beams while 
fans watched the arena's opening event. The arena's governing board 
instead chose to cancel the Los Angeles Lakers-Washington Wizards 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	All other events -- from minor league hockey games to an Elton  
John concert and pro wrestling match -- have been put on hold until 
engineers clear the arena as safe. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing this so we can get this behind us and get ready to  
have the events,'' said Gus Vratsinas, chief executive officer of 
the Vratsinas Construction Co., a partner in the joint venture 
building the arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you've got a concern, you do what we're doing -- not with  
people'' in the building, Vratsinas said as about 20 workers moved 
the water jugs into rows. 
</P>
<P>
	By Wednesday evening, workers had yet to fill even one seating  
section with the water containers. Once in place, the jugs and 
buckets were to sit there for four hours before being moved to 
another section. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's simulating having a load up there for the amount of time  
that we would have people up there,'' said the arena's general 
manager, Michael Marion. ``The weight we're putting up there is 
even more than we could put there with a bunch of 300-pound people, 
so we're overcompensating.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
