<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mixed; Gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mixed against other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0760 in latye European trading, up  
from $1.0642 Tuesday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the 
euro traded at $1.0758. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,  
included 107.38 Japanese yen, up from 106.23; 1.4780 Swiss francs, 
down from 1.4832;1.4809 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4744. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6526, down from $1.6534.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 107.41 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6530. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8177 German marks, down from 1.8219; 
6.0963 French francs, down from 6.1105; 2.0479 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.0528; 1,799.34 Italian lire, down from 1,803.70. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $321.00 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$318.50 on Tuesday. In Zurich the bid price was $321.50, up from 
$317.30. Gold in Hong Kong closed at $321.00 an ounce, down $2.50. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.62 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.57. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
