<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 14:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Businesses Thrive on Sox-Yankees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Pedro Martinez's final pitch was hardly in the  
catcher's mitt when Arthur D'Angelo swung into action. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no time for the 73-year-old Boston Red Sox souvenir  
dealer to celebrate Monday's victory over Cleveland. He expects to 
sell 25,000 T-shirts and hats for a first-ever American League 
Championship Series between the Red Sox and the New York Yankees 
this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Angelo spent a sleepless night at his Yawkey Way factory so  
that items could fill the shelves of The Souvenir Store by Tuesday 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the biggest thing that's ever going to hit this town  
in baseball,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than bragging rights are at stake when the 80-year-old  
rivalry finally gets played out in the postseason. Restauranteurs, 
hotel owners and retailers will make millions on the long-awaited 
showdown. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the rivalry inspires such passion that the windfall  
could be as much as 50 percent higher than it would be if the Red 
Sox were playing another team, according to local business 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a national event,'' said Patrick Moscaritolo,  
president of the Greater Boston Convention and Visitors Bureau. 
``That leads to a higher level of spending. Everyone wants a piece 
of the green.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moscaritolo said if three games are played in Boston -- a  
certainty if Boston wins one of the first four games in the 
seven-game series -- the local economy will get a $10 million boost, 
or about $3.3 million per game. 
</P>
<P>
	By comparison, the region pulled in about $1.5 million per game  
for two home games in the divisional series against Cleveland, 
Moscaritolo said. Had the Texas Rangers defeated New York in their 
best-of-5 series, the bureau says the economic boost would have 
been about $2 million per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Geographic and historic factors give a Red Sox-Yankees series  
greater value, Moscaritolo said. Until the advent of the wild-card 
playoff berth in 1995, it was impossible for the teams to face off 
in a playoff series because they compete in the same division. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans want to be part of a showdown that has roots in the days of  
Babe Ruth, Moscaritolo said. New Yorkers will make the relatively 
short trip to Boston to scalp tickets or just to soak in the 
atmosphere. Others will buy a cap or T-shirt. The visitors bureau 
estimates average spending per person on souvenirs by people who go 
to the games will increase from the usual $7 to $14. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything will increase in the relativity to the fact that  
it's the Yankees,'' Moscaritolo said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Sheraton Boston, the phone began ringing for reservations  
after Monday's game ended. The hotel, where the Indians stayed last 
week, is booked solid, said Mary Niester, director of sales and 
marketing. Niester won't say if the Yankees will be guests this 
weekend, citing confidentiality concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Niester said the hotel would have been full this weekend anyway  
because of the fall foliage season. But she said the series will 
lengthen the stays at the hotel, meaning the hotel will be booked 
on Thursday and Monday nights, when it normally wouldn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, Moscaritolo said, the demands of the national media  
and fans have meant calls to the visitors bureau for help placing 
hundreds of people in area hotels. 
</P>
<P>
	Given that these people have to eat somewhere, Ciobella  
restaurant executive host Brent Michael Kaufmann is preparing for 
two extra seatings a night. The Newbury Street restaurant has been 
visited by Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter and Red Sox shortstop 
Nomar Garciaparra, and Kaufmann expects some players to make 
appearances this weekend along with crowds of fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is definitely the best event I could think of this  
weekend,'' he said. ``There's nothing better that could happen for 
the hotels and restaurants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees-Red Sox series continues what's been an  
extraordinary year on the national sports scene for Boston. The 
region played host to the major league All-Star Game in July, and 
golf's prestigious Ryder Cup tournament last month. Moscaritolo 
estimates the region has raked in $300 million in visitor spending 
this year on such one-time sporting events, with the Yankees-Sox 
series set to add more to the pile. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a perfect matchup,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
