<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 07:45:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Keeps Money Policy Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's central bank decided on Wednesday to leave  
its monetary policy unchanged, but said it will begin purchasing 
short-term government bonds to make sure money keeps flowing 
through the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan has been under intense pressure from  
politicians at home as well as from other industrialized nations to 
ease its monetary policy in order to stem the yen's rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The move appeared to be more of an attempt to divert criticism  
than a dramatic change. 
</P>
<P>
	``The BOJ is fiddling at the edges with the existing policy, but  
this isn't a quantitative easing,'' said Russell Jones, chief 
economist for the Asia Pacific region at Lehman Brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	Brendan Brown, chief economist at Bank of Tokyo, however,  
welcomed the decision as ``a fairly significant set of steps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said that the move will increase liquidity, or reserves,  
in the banking system, which could lead to a rise in lending for 
investment and also help boost the economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Relaxing monetary policy usually helps bring a nation's currency  
down. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials have been worried about an overly strong yen  
because that hurts Japan's big exporters by reducing their overseas 
earnings. They believe that a soaring yen could throw off the 
nation's budding economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose above 107 yen on the news in trading in London,  
minutes after the announcement in Tokyo, up from 106.28 yen late 
Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The BOJ policy board meeting Wednesday was closely watched by  
financial markets here because it was the first since the meeting 
of finance ministers and central bankers from the Group of Seven 
major industrialized nations in Washington last month. 
</P>
<P>
	At the meeting, the Group of Seven called on Japan to further  
ease its monetary policy to make sure economic recovery continues. 
</P>
<P>
	The BOJ needs to ``carefully watch'' the yen, because a rise  
could hurt the recovery in private demand, BOJ Governor Masaru 
Hayami said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said that the worse was over for the Japanese economy.  
</P>
<P>
	``Compared with a month ago, I see slightly more bright signs,''  
he said after the meeting. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
