<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ConEd To Buy Northeast Utilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Consolidated Edison Inc. on Wednesday  
announced it was buying Northeast Utilities for about $3.5 billion 
in cash and stock, creating one of the largest electric companies 
in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal creates a company with more than 6.4 million electric  
and gas customers from New York City through New England. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said Wednesday that merging the two utilities  
could save $1.5 billion in operating expenses over 10 years. But 
they had no specifics on how those savings might affect the cost of 
heating and lighting homes and businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement is conditioned upon approvals from shareholders  
and state and federal regulators. Industry analysts said regulators 
weren't likely to allow the deal without some obvious benefit to 
consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eventually it should mean a decrease (in rates), because what  
they're doing is creating a regional super-utility,'' said Jim 
Coyne of Navagant Consulting Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is the latest example of consolidation in the utility  
industry as deregulation drives power distributors to seek 
competitive advantages by teaming up with neighbors. Just one day 
before, shareholders of Yankee Energy System Inc. accepted a $679 
million buyout from Northeast Utilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Eugene McGrath, chairman of Con Ed, said no layoffs were  
planned. Con Ed employs about 14,000 people in New York and 
northern New Jersey. Northeast has about 9,000 workers in 
Connecticut, Massachusetts and New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	New York City will serve as headquarters for the combined  
company, and McGrath will continue as chairman and chief executive 
officer; Northeast's corporate chief, Michael Morris, will be 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Northeast investors can exchange each of  
their shares for $25 in cash or $25 in Con Ed stock. Con Ed also 
will pay an additional $1 a share if the two working reactors at 
Northeast's troubled Millstone nuclear power plant in Connecticut 
are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Just weeks ago, Northeast pleaded guilty to 25 violations of  
federal law, including falsifying the credentials of control room 
operators, and agreed to pay $10 million -- the largest penalty in 
the history of the commercial nuclear power industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Northeast, based in Berlin, Conn., is the largest electric  
utility in New England with more than $4 billion in annual revenue 
and more than 1.7 million customers in Connecticut, Massachusetts, 
New Hampshire, Rhode Island, New York and Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Con Ed, based in New York, has more than 3.3 million electric  
customers and 1.4 million natural gas customers and has generated 
more than $7 billion in annual revenues in New York, New Jersey and 
Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Northeast Utilities stock rose Wednesday 43 3/4 cents to $21.68 3/4 on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where shares of Con Ed dipped 6 1/4 cents 
to $36.37 1/2. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
