<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 16:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seahawks Might Use Ahman Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) -- Mike Holmgren is thinking about giving  
Ricky Watters some help. 
</P>
<P>
	Watters, averaging a career-low 3.2 yards in Seattle's first  
four games, is matched against San Diego's stingy defense this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	His backup at running back, Ahman Green, has not had a carry  
this season because of fumbling problems during the Seahawks' 
exhibition games. He fumbled twice in each of the Seahawks' final 
two preseason starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Would I like to get him back in there? Certainly,'' Holmgren  
said Wednesday. ``Is this the week? I don't know yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Green, a third-round draft choice from Nebraska last year, had  
35 carries for 205 yards, an impressive 6.0 average, as a rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	At Nebraska, Green was a three-year starter who rushed for 3,880  
yards and 42 touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	In Holmgren's first season as coach, Green has been strictly a  
special-teams player, averaging 19.7 yards on 11 kickoff returns. 
He averaged 23 yards on 27 kickoff returns last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's faster than Ricky is,'' Holmgren said during his weekly  
news conference. ``He's probably a little more of an outside threat 
than Ricky. Ricky is an outstanding pass receiver and they balance 
each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it would be a nice changeup because I don't think  
they're the same type of back. Ricky is strong, big, he can carry 
the ball 30 times a game and handle that. Ahman would be more 
likely, if you blocked it correctly, to go 60, 70 yards, I would 
think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watters, in his ninth NFL season and second in Seattle, and the  
Seahawks' running attack could use a 60- or 70-yarder. Watters' 
longest gain this season has been 24 yards. His longest gain in 319 
carries in his first season here was 39 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the Seahawks (3-1) have won three in a row and share the  
lead in the AFC West with the Chargers, their running attack ranks 
27th in the NFL with 296 yards, or 74 yards per game. They have no 
rushing TDs and the team is averaging 2.8 yards on 104 carries. 
</P>
<P>
	At San Diego, they'll face a defense led by linebacker Junior  
Seau that is allowing 72.5 rushing yards per game. The Chargers 
have not allowed an opposing running back to rush for more than 100 
yards in 23 consecutive games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll see what happens,'' Holmgren said, obviously hoping to  
keep the Chargers coaching staff guessing this week. ``I know we're 
going to mix some people back in, but I don't know if this week 
he's (Green) going to play some more.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
